WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.410 --> 00:00:15.809
This will be Professor Cohen's kind of last
complete lecture, although, on the last day

00:00:15.809 --> 00:00:22.390
of classes the plan is we're going to take
some of the time just to talk over what we've

00:00:22.390 --> 00:00:24.930
done and review things.

00:00:24.930 --> 00:00:31.560
And it will be really oriented towards general
aspects of systems engineering.

00:00:31.560 --> 00:00:33.090
And, Aaron, I will turn it over to you.

00:00:33.090 --> 00:00:36.760
Thank you.

00:00:36.760 --> 00:00:45.520
Today, I'm going to lecture primarily on systems
engineering but management as it relates to

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:46.520
systems engineering.

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:50.030
I have several checks and balances.

00:00:50.030 --> 00:00:55.199
And, of course, today I've got people from
the Draper Laboratories and people from the

00:00:55.199 --> 00:01:01.780
predecessor to Draper Laboratories, MIT Instrumentation
Laboratory are going to check me to see if

00:01:01.780 --> 00:01:04.350
I say the right thing.

00:01:04.350 --> 00:01:10.340
First of all, I would like to say to you as
a class that I read your last submission reports

00:01:10.340 --> 00:01:13.470
and really thought they were outstanding.

00:01:13.470 --> 00:01:19.100
They show a great deal of interest, a great
deal of understanding and a great deal of

00:01:19.100 --> 00:01:20.100
initiative.

00:01:20.100 --> 00:01:21.100
And so, I really compliment you.

00:01:21.100 --> 00:01:27.780
And I'm sure your final reports will be better,
but they really were very, very, very good.

00:01:27.780 --> 00:01:36.570
You've heard a lot of people talk previously,
starting with, in my way of thinking, Dale

00:01:36.570 --> 00:01:41.910
Myers who was sort of the person who started
the program in Washington at the time.

00:01:41.910 --> 00:01:47.440
You didn't hear from another very important
man, George Miller, who was really Dale's

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:50.720
boss at the time.

00:01:50.720 --> 00:01:54.349
But George is still alive, is still doing
very well.

00:01:54.349 --> 00:01:55.789
And you didn't hear from a lot of other people.

00:01:55.789 --> 00:02:03.360
You did hear from Chris Kraft which sort of
set the tone, you might say, for a very interesting

00:02:03.360 --> 00:02:09.229
and understanding man who really knows what
he's doing and says what he thinks.

00:02:09.229 --> 00:02:13.950
But there are several other people that I
would like to talk about that had a great

00:02:13.950 --> 00:02:18.550
bearing on my career in terms of systems engineering.

00:02:18.550 --> 00:02:23.030
There were two people, both who have passed
away.

00:02:23.030 --> 00:02:25.530
One is Joe Shea.

00:02:25.530 --> 00:02:29.340
And Joe was a very remarkable engineer.

00:02:29.340 --> 00:02:38.270
He was program manager of the Apollo Program
at the Johnson Space Center, then left and

00:02:38.270 --> 00:02:44.870
became Vice President of Raytheon here and
then became a professor at MIT in the Aero-Astro

00:02:44.870 --> 00:02:45.870
Department.

00:02:45.870 --> 00:02:49.890
And I thought he maybe taught the forerunner
to this course.

00:02:49.890 --> 00:02:52.100
He taught systems engineering.

00:02:52.100 --> 00:02:59.190
And Joe Shea was actually the best systems
engineer I've ever met, so I am going to talk

00:02:59.190 --> 00:03:03.340
a little bit and give you some understanding
of my interaction with Joe.

00:03:03.340 --> 00:03:07.640
The best job I ever had, you might say, really,
is I've had a lot of different jobs, but my

00:03:07.640 --> 00:03:14.120
first job was really working with the MIT
Instrumentation Laboratory where I met a great

00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:15.200
number of people.

00:03:15.200 --> 00:03:19.860
I'm not going to mention everybody because
it would fill up the time.

00:03:19.860 --> 00:03:25.660
They taught me systems engineering, but had
it not been for the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory

00:03:25.660 --> 00:03:29.010
we wouldn't have gone to the Moon on the schedule
we went on.

00:03:29.010 --> 00:03:31.780
They really did a fantastic job, all these
people.

00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:34.670
I mean they were just you might say giants.

00:03:34.670 --> 00:03:39.290
There were great people at Rockwell, at North
American Aviation such as George Jeffs and

00:03:39.290 --> 00:03:47.090
great people at Grumman such as Joe Gavin
and other places, but I have to say that the

00:03:47.090 --> 00:03:53.230
MIT Instrumentation Lab really carried the
ball on understanding how to do guidance,

00:03:53.230 --> 00:03:54.880
navigation and control.

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:59.940
And if you read some of the comments by George
Low, who is the other person I am going to

00:03:59.940 --> 00:04:01.900
talk about, George Low is another giant.

00:04:01.900 --> 00:04:07.090
He says the most complicated system on the
Apollo spacecraft was the guidance navigation

00:04:07.090 --> 00:04:08.390
system, if you read what he said.

00:04:08.390 --> 00:04:15.310
And could you really hit a target 240,000
miles away and bring it back?

00:04:15.310 --> 00:04:18.739
But let me get back to Joe Shea.

00:04:18.739 --> 00:04:22.030
I said he was a great systems engineer.

00:04:22.030 --> 00:04:25.910
And Joe Shea taught me a couple of things.

00:04:25.910 --> 00:04:29.790
One, he taught me not to be afraid to make
a decision.

00:04:29.790 --> 00:04:36.430
He said the fact that you are in charge, the
fact that you have looked at all the information,

00:04:36.430 --> 00:04:41.260
the fact that you know the details, you are
the best one to make a decision.

00:04:41.260 --> 00:04:48.890
And if you could make a timely decision and
your battering average is a little over 60%

00:04:48.890 --> 00:04:50.850
you're doing very well.

00:04:50.850 --> 00:04:56.351
But the fact you made it timely and the fact
that you understand it, you can make a change.

00:04:56.351 --> 00:04:58.970
You can change if you are wrong.

00:04:58.970 --> 00:05:01.710
And that always stuck with me, not to be afraid
to make a decision.

00:05:01.710 --> 00:05:08.070
Because many times as you go through your
role in systems engineering you're not going

00:05:08.070 --> 00:05:11.419
to have all the information to make a decision
on a timely basis.

00:05:11.419 --> 00:05:17.810
It is just not going to be there, especially
if you do a program that pertains to advanced

00:05:17.810 --> 00:05:21.590
technology, advanced research and development.

00:05:21.590 --> 00:05:23.420
That is one thing that is important.

00:05:23.420 --> 00:05:27.190
Another thing that Joe Shea brought to the
table.

00:05:27.190 --> 00:05:32.960
During the Apollo Program, before we had Joe
Shea, we would sit around a conference table

00:05:32.960 --> 00:05:39.210
in the early `60s trying to figure out what
systems engineering was, but we couldn't really

00:05:39.210 --> 00:05:41.650
explain what we had to do.

00:05:41.650 --> 00:05:44.010
We didn't know what we really had to do.

00:05:44.010 --> 00:05:54.080
But when Joe Shea came, he brought with him
the insight of what you needed to do to do

00:05:54.080 --> 00:05:55.080
systems engineering.

00:05:55.080 --> 00:06:01.320
Now, this is the Apollo stack as you see in
on the pad you might say.

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:03.090
The launch vehicles.

00:06:03.090 --> 00:06:04.500
The launch vehicle.

00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:06.949
The first stage, second stage.

00:06:06.949 --> 00:06:15.060
Then you get to the lunar module, the command
and service module, launch escape tower.

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:17.330
That is what it looks like on the pad.

00:06:17.330 --> 00:06:23.300
Well, Joe Shea gave me probably the toughest
job and one of the most important jobs that

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:26.030
I had in my career.

00:06:26.030 --> 00:06:33.220
He said, Aaron, you are going to be in charge
of resolving all the ICDs, the interface control

00:06:33.220 --> 00:06:34.220
documents.

00:06:34.220 --> 00:06:39.290
That is all the interfaces between all the
stages, between the command and service module

00:06:39.290 --> 00:06:44.130
and the lunar module, between the command
and service module, lunar module and the stack,

00:06:44.130 --> 00:06:47.790
between the command and service module, lunar
module and the launch complex.

00:06:47.790 --> 00:06:52.330
There were about a thousand ICDs involved
in that.

00:06:52.330 --> 00:06:59.770
And that was a formidable task because an
interface control document you cannot design

00:06:59.770 --> 00:07:04.009
without the interfaces being defined, and
you cannot define the interfaces without the

00:07:04.009 --> 00:07:05.020
design.

00:07:05.020 --> 00:07:08.150
So it is really a chicken and the egg type
of thing.

00:07:08.150 --> 00:07:11.550
And it turns out that was a turning point
in my career because we did do that.

00:07:11.550 --> 00:07:16.490
In fact, a little sideline, a little interesting
story.

00:07:16.490 --> 00:07:20.070
He anointed me to do this job but didn't just
leave me there.

00:07:20.070 --> 00:07:24.800
He took me to the contractors, he took me
to the MIT Instrumentation Lab, he took me

00:07:24.800 --> 00:07:29.820
to Rockwell, he took me to Grumman and he
took me to the Marshall Space Flight Center

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:32.370
and Kennedy Space Center.

00:07:32.370 --> 00:07:36.210
And the funny part about it, he took me in
to see von Braun, which I didn't know about.

00:07:36.210 --> 00:07:38.620
I didn't know von Braun.

00:07:38.620 --> 00:07:41.750
And he said, Wernher, this is Aaron Cohen.

00:07:41.750 --> 00:07:44.699
We were in his big office at Marshall.

00:07:44.699 --> 00:07:48.680
He said he is going to resolve all the ICDs,
all the interface control documents.

00:07:48.680 --> 00:07:50.770
And Wernher von Braun said that is wonderful.

00:07:50.770 --> 00:07:52.100
What is an ICD?

00:07:52.100 --> 00:07:58.600
So I knew I had a problem there right away
that the head charge of Marshall didn't know

00:07:58.600 --> 00:07:59.650
what an ICD was.

00:07:59.650 --> 00:08:02.699
But that was a little bit of a sideline on
it.

00:08:02.699 --> 00:08:08.580
I did have the job to actually resolve all
the interface control documents.

00:08:08.580 --> 00:08:14.270
And that turned out to be one of my most interesting,
most challenging jobs as a young engineer.

00:08:14.270 --> 00:08:19.639
It really taught me systems engineering, because
one of the important parts of system engineering

00:08:19.639 --> 00:08:23.310
is understanding where the interfaces are
and how you get the interfaces resolved.

00:08:23.310 --> 00:08:29.380
And you could imagine trying to get Grumman
at that time at North American Aviation and

00:08:29.380 --> 00:08:33.539
MIT Instrumental Labs to agree on an interface
document.

00:08:33.539 --> 00:08:37.130
I mean it wasn't the easiest thing in the
world to do.

00:08:37.130 --> 00:08:38.130
Yes.

00:08:38.130 --> 00:08:39.440
Did you have a question?

00:08:39.440 --> 00:08:43.259
I was just wondering, aside from technically
making sure that the interfaces are working

00:08:43.259 --> 00:08:47.509
and everything, what is involved in resolving
an ICD?

00:08:47.509 --> 00:08:49.410
That's a good question.

00:08:49.410 --> 00:08:52.429
Well, first of all, I am going to talk a little
bit more about ICDs in general.

00:08:52.429 --> 00:08:55.300
ICDs you can define in several categories.

00:08:55.300 --> 00:09:01.800
One is mechanical or physical ICDs, bolt hold
patterns, just how things bolt together.

00:09:01.800 --> 00:09:07.569
The other, you might say, is electrical ICDs,
what kind of electrical signals are sent and

00:09:07.569 --> 00:09:09.490
electrical interfaces.

00:09:09.490 --> 00:09:12.449
And the other are functional ICDs.

00:09:12.449 --> 00:09:19.920
One of the big ICDs we had to resolve was
a term called Guidance Reference Release.

00:09:19.920 --> 00:09:24.790
Marshal had an inertial measurement unit in
their instrument unit, and we had to have

00:09:24.790 --> 00:09:30.620
that synchronized with our system or with
the system in the command and service module.

00:09:30.620 --> 00:09:34.110
What is involved in it is you sit down and
you talk.

00:09:34.110 --> 00:09:36.819
You have a draft ICD.

00:09:36.819 --> 00:09:37.959
And we had these big meetings.

00:09:37.959 --> 00:09:41.309
We had them at the Kennedy Space Center.

00:09:41.309 --> 00:09:44.490
I don't know if you've ever been to the Kennedy
Space Center, but we actually fill the firing

00:09:44.490 --> 00:09:46.730
room with people.

00:09:46.730 --> 00:09:52.269
And each group had a certain set of draft
ICDs, and they would sit down in working groups

00:09:52.269 --> 00:09:59.279
and decide what had to be done to get the
interface compatible in terms of the three

00:09:59.279 --> 00:10:05.690
phases Physical, electrical and functional.

00:10:05.690 --> 00:10:06.770
And you just work out the details.

00:10:06.770 --> 00:10:11.019
Aaron, probably now in the 21st century, we
ought to add data ICDs.

00:10:11.019 --> 00:10:12.019
Data ICDs, yeah.

00:10:12.019 --> 00:10:16.319
Well, now things have changed probably a lot
since I've been involved in it.

00:10:16.319 --> 00:10:17.949
I mean remember Mars Polar Lander.

00:10:17.949 --> 00:10:19.749
We had English units coming over.

00:10:19.749 --> 00:10:20.749
Yeah, that's right.

00:10:20.749 --> 00:10:23.100
And the people thought they were getting metric
units.

00:10:23.100 --> 00:10:24.100
So the data ICDs are also critical.

00:10:24.100 --> 00:10:29.100
You know, and a lot of things are very simple
and mundane.

00:10:29.100 --> 00:10:30.579
I could tell you a story with the crew.

00:10:30.579 --> 00:10:34.319
When we said you're going to have in-flight
maintenance with the crew.

00:10:34.319 --> 00:10:42.779
And we gave the crew to change out a component,
but instead of taking the screw out very easily,

00:10:42.779 --> 00:10:47.970
we had actually put Loctite in the screw so
we couldn't undo the screw.

00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:51.629
There are very simple interfaces that have
to be resolved.

00:10:51.629 --> 00:10:53.540
Some are mundane, some are very sophisticated.

00:10:53.540 --> 00:10:55.410
I don't know if that answers your question.

00:10:55.410 --> 00:10:57.540
The problem is there is no F=ma.

00:10:57.540 --> 00:11:02.689
There is no closed form solution that tells
you exactly how to do it.

00:11:02.689 --> 00:11:08.709
You just have to sit down and work it because
the design hasn't been complete but you have

00:11:08.709 --> 00:11:09.709
ideas.

00:11:09.709 --> 00:11:13.179
You float ideas, you negotiate, you arbitrate
and then you come up with a decision.

00:11:13.179 --> 00:11:17.550
The main thing is you've got to make a decision,
and somebody has to be there to make a decision.

00:11:17.550 --> 00:11:23.000
That was my job, to make a decision.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:29.079
That was what Joe Shea left me with.

00:11:29.079 --> 00:11:37.600
And people that know him will agree that he
was an outstanding engineer but also probably

00:11:37.600 --> 00:11:40.550
one of the best systems engineers.

00:11:40.550 --> 00:11:45.920
Larry, do you know what course Joe taught
when he was here?

00:11:45.920 --> 00:11:47.939
Yes, systems engineering.

00:11:47.939 --> 00:11:50.619
He taught this course?

00:11:50.619 --> 00:11:51.619
Yes.

00:11:51.619 --> 00:11:56.759
I thought he taught this course because I
know I came up and gave a lecture for him.

00:11:56.759 --> 00:11:59.259
Until he was taken ill.

00:11:59.259 --> 00:12:08.649
Let me talk about another person that was
very prominent in informing my career.

00:12:08.649 --> 00:12:10.429
His name was George Low.

00:12:10.429 --> 00:12:20.549
After Joe retired, George Low became the Apollo
Program Manager at the Johnson Space Center.

00:12:20.549 --> 00:12:23.949
And George was very much a disciplinarian.

00:12:23.949 --> 00:12:27.279
He always had time to see you.

00:12:27.279 --> 00:12:31.809
But there were several criteria in seeing
you.

00:12:31.809 --> 00:12:41.930
You had to tell him what your subject was,
how long he wanted and why you wanted to see

00:12:41.930 --> 00:12:42.930
him.

00:12:42.930 --> 00:12:46.600
So when you met with him, if you asked for
15 minutes, you had 15 minutes.

00:12:46.600 --> 00:12:50.509
And no matter how important the job was, if
you didn't finish was you had to say in 15

00:12:50.509 --> 00:12:52.559
minutes you were out the door.

00:12:52.559 --> 00:12:55.259
And you only did that once.

00:12:55.259 --> 00:12:59.110
But you didn't ask for too much time either
because you got penalized if you said you

00:12:59.110 --> 00:13:00.850
needed an hour and you only took 30 minutes.

00:13:00.850 --> 00:13:05.759
So, he was very much a disciplinarian.

00:13:05.759 --> 00:13:11.060
He actually, after he retired from NASA, after
he retired from the Apollo Program became

00:13:11.060 --> 00:13:17.589
Deputy Administrator at NASA and was very
instrumental in the Shuttle Program and then

00:13:17.589 --> 00:13:20.480
retired and became president of Rensselaer
Polytechnic Institute.

00:13:20.480 --> 00:13:22.670
So, George had a very illustrious career.

00:13:22.670 --> 00:13:25.649
He passed away several years ago.

00:13:25.649 --> 00:13:31.139
One incident might be of interest to you,
and I recall it very vividly.

00:13:31.139 --> 00:13:40.180
I don't know if everybody else does, but we
were getting ready to go to the Moon on Apollo

00:13:40.180 --> 00:13:41.180
11.

00:13:41.180 --> 00:13:42.180
This is on Apollo.

00:13:42.180 --> 00:13:44.980
And you monitor all the systems very carefully.

00:13:44.980 --> 00:13:51.589
And we were monitoring the inertial measurement
unit in the lunar module which is right here.

00:13:51.589 --> 00:13:57.079
And for some reason or other the drift rate
changed fairly drastically.

00:13:57.079 --> 00:14:00.040
Now, it was still in spec.

00:14:00.040 --> 00:14:04.930
The drift rate was still in spec but it changed.

00:14:04.930 --> 00:14:09.989
And to get to the lunar module and change
out an inertial measurement unit on the pad

00:14:09.989 --> 00:14:10.989
is pretty hard to do.

00:14:10.989 --> 00:14:13.600
First of all, the lunar module has very little
structure to it.

00:14:13.600 --> 00:14:15.509
It is made out of Reynolds Wrap really.

00:14:15.509 --> 00:14:18.470
I mean it doesn't have very much structure
to it.

00:14:18.470 --> 00:14:25.920
And so we reviewed it with all the people
involved, reviewed the data and we concluded

00:14:25.920 --> 00:14:29.180
very clearly that there was nothing wrong
with it.

00:14:29.180 --> 00:14:38.559
And so we went to George Low and we told him
a unified story, the MIT people, the MIT Instrumentation

00:14:38.559 --> 00:14:41.939
people, the Rockwell people, everybody, the
JSC people.

00:14:41.939 --> 00:14:48.360
And George Low listened very attentively and
then said can you explain why it changed?

00:14:48.360 --> 00:14:52.420
And we said no, we're going to change it out.

00:14:52.420 --> 00:14:58.189
That is the thing that always stuck in my
mind.

00:14:58.189 --> 00:15:03.860
If there is something that you don't understand
then you need to take some action to fix it.

00:15:03.860 --> 00:15:09.489
And to me that was a very important part of
my learning process.

00:15:09.489 --> 00:15:20.299
And so, those were the people you might say
that really had an effect on my systems engineering

00:15:20.299 --> 00:15:22.199
thought process.

00:15:22.199 --> 00:15:28.040
The other thing I want to talk about with
you today is you heard a lot of people talk

00:15:28.040 --> 00:15:32.889
that I would class as subsystem managers.

00:15:32.889 --> 00:15:35.329
You heard Tom Moser talk about structures.

00:15:35.329 --> 00:15:36.329
I don't know if I can recall them all.

00:15:36.329 --> 00:15:40.299
Al Louviere talk about the mechanical systems.

00:15:40.299 --> 00:15:47.449
You heard Bob Ried talk about aerothermodynamics,
Bass Redd about aerodynamics, Henry Pohl about

00:15:47.449 --> 00:15:53.249
reaction control systems, auxiliary power
units and hydraulics, Walt Guy about environmental

00:15:53.249 --> 00:15:54.269
control systems.

00:15:54.269 --> 00:15:55.619
You heard of these people.

00:15:55.619 --> 00:16:02.829
These people are what I call subsystem managers
that actually, in some regards, work for me

00:16:02.829 --> 00:16:05.519
and, in some regards, didn't work for me.

00:16:05.519 --> 00:16:08.439
And that is what you call a matrix management
system.

00:16:08.439 --> 00:16:10.739
Now, I'm going to talk about matrix management.

00:16:10.739 --> 00:16:16.629
Matrix management was actually a very popular
management system several years ago.

00:16:16.629 --> 00:16:22.220
I don't know if it is used today or not, but
matrix management is a type of management

00:16:22.220 --> 00:16:25.899
basically used by large organizations.

00:16:25.899 --> 00:16:31.989
Primarily what it is are large projects organized
with teams that work on a functional rather

00:16:31.989 --> 00:16:36.730
than a project basis.

00:16:36.730 --> 00:16:41.369
In other words, these people I just talked
about actually had two bosses.

00:16:41.369 --> 00:16:49.470
They had a boss in their engineering organization,
a very famous man named Max Faget.

00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:52.619
And then they had another boss, which was
so famous, me.

00:16:52.619 --> 00:16:58.660
And I was their boss that controlled the project's
cost schedule and performance.

00:16:58.660 --> 00:17:01.040
And they actually reported to me on that.

00:17:01.040 --> 00:17:03.230
But they actually had two bosses.

00:17:03.230 --> 00:17:06.089
And so, you do that for several reasons.

00:17:06.089 --> 00:17:08.799
You do that in order to conserve resources.

00:17:08.799 --> 00:17:12.690
And many large companies do that.

00:17:12.690 --> 00:17:19.050
The other way of doing it, actually, would
be to put all that engineering talent in the

00:17:19.050 --> 00:17:20.640
project office.

00:17:20.640 --> 00:17:22.270
And you could see the advantages and disadvantages.

00:17:22.270 --> 00:17:25.930
I will show you more explicitly the advantages
and disadvantages on that.

00:17:25.930 --> 00:17:29.940
The advantages are that you have a dedicated
organization.

00:17:29.940 --> 00:17:33.860
The disadvantages are that when the project
is over there is no place for these people

00:17:33.860 --> 00:17:34.920
to go.

00:17:34.920 --> 00:17:37.550
And I don't know what you use.

00:17:37.550 --> 00:17:40.730
You have a matrix at the Draper Labs today.

00:17:40.730 --> 00:17:42.410
I'm not that close to industry.

00:17:42.410 --> 00:17:43.550
Do most companies use matrix today?

00:17:43.550 --> 00:17:44.550
Yes, most aerospace companies.

00:17:44.550 --> 00:17:54.740
There are too many projects that change all
the time and somebody has to be responsible

00:17:54.740 --> 00:17:56.240
for the people.

00:17:56.240 --> 00:17:58.730
See, that's an interesting part.

00:17:58.730 --> 00:18:01.460
We, at the Johnson Space Center, didn't have
that many projects.

00:18:01.460 --> 00:18:05.890
We only had really maybe one or two projects,
but we still used matrix management because

00:18:05.890 --> 00:18:10.460
there is a check and balance on matrix management
which you don't get on centralized or project

00:18:10.460 --> 00:18:11.460
management.

00:18:11.460 --> 00:18:12.530
There is advantage to it.

00:18:12.530 --> 00:18:14.320
There are some disadvantages to it.

00:18:14.320 --> 00:18:18.900
His rotation lab was project-oriented at the
time when we did Apollo.

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:23.770
You were project-oriented because you had
one project and you were just project-oriented

00:18:23.770 --> 00:18:24.890
all NASA project.

00:18:24.890 --> 00:18:27.140
So, there are advantages and disadvantages.

00:18:27.140 --> 00:18:34.160
I had some dealings with Ford Motor Company,
and I think Ford Motor Company actually uses

00:18:34.160 --> 00:18:35.160
matrix management.

00:18:35.160 --> 00:18:39.740
I think most large companies use matrix management
today.

00:18:39.740 --> 00:18:45.061
Anyway, that's really the advantages and disadvantages
of matrix management.

00:18:45.061 --> 00:18:50.530
And a lot of things I have already said.

00:18:50.530 --> 00:18:57.390
Under matrix management, all the people who
do one type of work are in a pool.

00:18:57.390 --> 00:19:03.280
For example, all the engineers in one engineering
department report to an engineering manager.

00:19:03.280 --> 00:19:04.310
That is what I said.

00:19:04.310 --> 00:19:05.890
They all report to an engineering manager.

00:19:05.890 --> 00:19:07.570
In this case, the name was Max Faget.

00:19:07.570 --> 00:19:12.230
And if you do history in the Space Program,
Max Faget becomes a very prominent name.

00:19:12.230 --> 00:19:19.870
He was really, you might say, the original
designer of the Mercury, Gemini and a lot

00:19:19.870 --> 00:19:22.690
to the Apollo spacecraft configuration.

00:19:22.690 --> 00:19:25.090
So, you will run into his name time and time
again.

00:19:25.090 --> 00:19:32.390
But, the interesting part about it is that
Max and I used to go at it tooth and nail.

00:19:32.390 --> 00:19:36.620
I mean his people would want to do something
like a Walt Guy.

00:19:36.620 --> 00:19:41.200
Walt at that time was a very stubborn person.

00:19:41.200 --> 00:19:44.340
And he would want to do something and I wouldn't
want to do it.

00:19:44.340 --> 00:19:46.560
Well, he would go to Max.

00:19:46.560 --> 00:19:51.120
And then Max and I and Walt would have a meeting
at the Summit with Chris Kraft.

00:19:51.120 --> 00:19:52.550
It was a common point.

00:19:52.550 --> 00:19:55.180
We all went to see Chris Kraft.

00:19:55.180 --> 00:19:59.780
Sometimes I won and sometimes I lost, but
I learned actually to love it.

00:19:59.780 --> 00:20:04.051
Even though it frustrated me, I learned to
love it because there was that check and balance

00:20:04.051 --> 00:20:08.610
on me that I could not do something that was
going to actually be wrong.

00:20:08.610 --> 00:20:11.350
Somebody else was going to catch me if I did
something wrong.

00:20:11.350 --> 00:20:17.160
Now, I honestly do not know today what NASA
uses, whether they use matrix management on

00:20:17.160 --> 00:20:21.350
the Shuttle program or on the Space Station
program or how they are going to do it.

00:20:21.350 --> 00:20:23.110
Do you have any idea?

00:20:23.110 --> 00:20:27.240
The Shuttle was certainly much more project-oriented.

00:20:27.240 --> 00:20:32.560
We don't have the same, I mean there is an
engineering division at JSC, but during the

00:20:32.560 --> 00:20:36.410
Shuttle that was -- It started out matrix
management.

00:20:36.410 --> 00:20:42.710
I think it really decreased, and there was
no more Max Faget running things in that same

00:20:42.710 --> 00:20:43.710
way.

00:20:43.710 --> 00:20:49.500
And so that, in my mind, at least in my way
of thinking, is probably one reason why problems

00:20:49.500 --> 00:20:54.200
occurs, because you don't have that independent
check and balance.

00:20:54.200 --> 00:21:00.810
There is a very good reason why matrix management,
I think, is important, even though you don't

00:21:00.810 --> 00:21:10.280
have a number of projects that would cause
you to do matrix management.

00:21:10.280 --> 00:21:13.490
Well, this says these same engineers may be
assigned to different projects and report

00:21:13.490 --> 00:21:16.110
to a project manager while working on that
project.

00:21:16.110 --> 00:21:20.510
Therefore, each engineer may have to work
under several managers to get his or her job

00:21:20.510 --> 00:21:21.510
done.

00:21:21.510 --> 00:21:22.510
And that is what I was saying.

00:21:22.510 --> 00:21:31.660
It just turns out that you do have that type
of problem in doing that.

00:21:31.660 --> 00:21:34.260
Proponents suggest there are two advantages
to matrix management.

00:21:34.260 --> 00:21:38.110
First, it allows team members to share information
more readily across task boundaries.

00:21:38.110 --> 00:21:43.550
Second, it allows for a specialization that
can increase the depth of knowledge.

00:21:43.550 --> 00:21:48.590
You can see how, if you have a matrix manager,
you can call on more resources to go back

00:21:48.590 --> 00:21:54.990
to your home organization facilities in terms
of testing.

00:21:54.990 --> 00:22:00.650
I have worked under, and when I was in industry,
total project organizations.

00:22:00.650 --> 00:22:04.010
And it has a lot of advantages and disadvantages
also.

00:22:04.010 --> 00:22:10.230
The disadvantage of matrix management is that
employees can be confused due to conflicting

00:22:10.230 --> 00:22:11.230
loyalties.

00:22:11.230 --> 00:22:15.550
I mean was Walt Guy loyal to Max Faget or
was he loyal to Aaron Cohen?

00:22:15.550 --> 00:22:30.930
Now, Max actually gave him in raises but 
I controlled the dollars for the project.

00:22:30.930 --> 00:22:33.190
But, you're right, that is what counts.

00:22:33.190 --> 00:22:34.190
They call that pink ticket.

00:22:34.190 --> 00:22:37.870
He was actually pink ticketed to Max and actually
worked for me.

00:22:37.870 --> 00:22:49.060
And I had to use all my persuasion to get
him to do the type of job.

00:22:49.060 --> 00:22:55.550
Properly management cooperative environment,
however, can neutralize these disadvantages.

00:22:55.550 --> 00:22:59.360
In Apollo there was one program.

00:22:59.360 --> 00:23:00.360
Right.

00:23:00.360 --> 00:23:01.580
[AUDIENCE QUESTION]

00:23:01.580 --> 00:23:08.220
For example, we had Air Force, Navy and NASA.

00:23:08.220 --> 00:23:09.220
Right.

00:23:09.220 --> 00:23:15.040
And we were doing accuracy evaluation for
each one.

00:23:15.040 --> 00:23:20.250
And we were developing the whole software
from scratch for each one.

00:23:20.250 --> 00:23:24.870
It was different language and different computers
and you couldn't compare results.

00:23:24.870 --> 00:23:25.870
Right.

00:23:25.870 --> 00:23:31.530
And when you have one engineering organization
that does the same at least you can compare.

00:23:31.530 --> 00:23:33.330
You have the check and balance.

00:23:33.330 --> 00:23:34.330
Right.

00:23:34.330 --> 00:23:35.600
That's a very good point.

00:23:35.600 --> 00:23:36.600
Yes, Jerry.

00:23:36.600 --> 00:23:37.600
[AUDIENCE QUESTION]

00:23:37.600 --> 00:23:43.100
Whether you a project organization, you had
your thumb on the people who had to produce.

00:23:43.100 --> 00:23:50.040
In the matrix organization, off times the
engineering manager would shuffle his man

00:23:50.040 --> 00:23:53.260
right out from under you to another project.

00:23:53.260 --> 00:23:55.630
Oh, that's right.

00:23:55.630 --> 00:23:57.880
That's what I had to contend with.

00:23:57.880 --> 00:24:05.010
On the other hand, my strong personality and
my good will kept it from going that way.

00:24:05.010 --> 00:24:10.050
And there was a certain amount of esprit de
corps that they wanted to get the job done.

00:24:10.050 --> 00:24:14.010
In the end it is the people.

00:24:14.010 --> 00:24:15.400
It's the people.

00:24:15.400 --> 00:24:17.370
It doesn't matter what organization.

00:24:17.370 --> 00:24:18.370
That's right.

00:24:18.370 --> 00:24:22.770
If the people are wrong, no organization is
going to work.

00:24:22.770 --> 00:24:23.770
Well, that's absolutely right.

00:24:23.770 --> 00:24:24.770
You have to have the right people.

00:24:24.770 --> 00:24:27.620
Well, that's why I brought some of these people
to talk to these students because these people

00:24:27.620 --> 00:24:29.310
were the people I worked with.

00:24:29.310 --> 00:24:31.710
Even though we argued at times.

00:24:31.710 --> 00:24:38.500
There was nobody that argued more than Henry
Pohl and I did, but he is usually always right.

00:24:38.500 --> 00:24:44.660
But you can learn to live with it.

00:24:44.660 --> 00:24:48.650
Matrix management can put some difficult on
the project managers because they must work

00:24:48.650 --> 00:24:52.160
closely with other managers and workers in
order to complete the project.

00:24:52.160 --> 00:24:54.900
The functional mangers may have different
goals and objectives.

00:24:54.900 --> 00:25:00.640
I was saying this as I present these charts,
but I think you can visualize that.

00:25:00.640 --> 00:25:03.790
And don't hesitate to ask questions because
you've got a lot of people here in the room

00:25:03.790 --> 00:25:06.410
today that can help answer these questions.

00:25:06.410 --> 00:25:07.410
Yes.

00:25:07.410 --> 00:25:09.810
The point about checking and balance.

00:25:09.810 --> 00:25:11.750
You have several managers.

00:25:11.750 --> 00:25:12.750
Yes.

00:25:12.750 --> 00:25:19.510
From my understanding, you have maybe a functional
manager and then you have [OVERLAPPING VOICES].

00:25:19.510 --> 00:25:22.110
Well, let me tell you what I mean by check
and balance.

00:25:22.110 --> 00:25:25.330
Let me give you a specific example.

00:25:25.330 --> 00:25:30.760
Let's say Henry Pohl on the reaction control
system wanted to do more testing or wanted

00:25:30.760 --> 00:25:33.330
to do more stability testing.

00:25:33.330 --> 00:25:38.110
And I looked at my budget and I looked at
where we stood in the schedule, and I said

00:25:38.110 --> 00:25:41.390
we just cannot afford that, we're just not
going to do that.

00:25:41.390 --> 00:25:42.990
I made an arbitrary decision.

00:25:42.990 --> 00:25:50.620
Well, Henry would be very upset about that
and he would go to Max, his functional manager.

00:25:50.620 --> 00:25:54.510
And Max would say boy, you're right, Aaron
is crazy.

00:25:54.510 --> 00:26:01.230
He would then call a meeting with Chris Kraft
between Henry, Max and myself to decide what

00:26:01.230 --> 00:26:02.310
we were going to do.

00:26:02.310 --> 00:26:04.400
And then Chris was the final word, the man
you met.

00:26:04.400 --> 00:26:05.970
He's a pretty strong guy.

00:26:05.970 --> 00:26:11.610
And if he agreed with Max, if Max had a convincing
story, he would turn me around and then we

00:26:11.610 --> 00:26:12.610
would do the testing.

00:26:12.610 --> 00:26:14.470
And I would just have to find the money some
place.

00:26:14.470 --> 00:26:22.540
But if I could convince Chris that Max was
overdoing it then I would win.

00:26:22.540 --> 00:26:23.540
And normally I lost, but that is OK.

00:26:23.540 --> 00:26:29.120
Do the engineers in any of these organizations
out of matrix management feel that they have

00:26:29.120 --> 00:26:30.690
too many managers?

00:26:30.690 --> 00:26:33.820
Well, it is frustrating to them a little bit.

00:26:33.820 --> 00:26:34.820
Yes, they did.

00:26:34.820 --> 00:26:40.090
It's frustrating because they had to feel
that they were working for two different people.

00:26:40.090 --> 00:26:44.170
And it is a little bit confusing to them.

00:26:44.170 --> 00:26:45.910
I mean they had two loyalties.

00:26:45.910 --> 00:26:47.360
That's what I pointed out.

00:26:47.360 --> 00:26:49.310
They essentially had two different loyalties.

00:26:49.310 --> 00:26:55.650
One to their functional manager who paid their
salaries and the other to me who really had

00:26:55.650 --> 00:26:59.210
the money for the project and the schedule.

00:26:59.210 --> 00:27:02.070
So, yes, it is a very tough thing to do.

00:27:02.070 --> 00:27:07.530
But, as you could tell, by talking to these
people that experienced it both in Apollo

00:27:07.530 --> 00:27:12.610
and in the early days of Shuttle, they were
very satisfied with the results.

00:27:12.610 --> 00:27:22.250
That is why it is very frustrating to some
of us to see the way things are going because

00:27:22.250 --> 00:27:27.860
we carried over most of these people you talked
to or are here in the room today worked on

00:27:27.860 --> 00:27:32.590
Apollo and then went and worked on Shuttle.

00:27:32.590 --> 00:27:34.830
We had the same process.

00:27:34.830 --> 00:27:53.580
We had the same Joe Shea, George Low process
that we did.

00:27:53.580 --> 00:27:56.550
Yes.

00:27:56.550 --> 00:28:02.490
[AUDIENCE QUESTION]

00:28:02.490 --> 00:28:14.380
Well, that's absolutely true.

00:28:14.380 --> 00:28:19.940
Your decision-making process in matrix management
turns out to be a little bit more cumbersome

00:28:19.940 --> 00:28:23.320
than if you have direct control.

00:28:23.320 --> 00:28:28.800
In other words, if you have your thumb on
everybody you can get a decision pretty quickly.

00:28:28.800 --> 00:28:35.700
On the other hand, you can violate some good
checks and balances so you give up the process

00:28:35.700 --> 00:28:41.250
of a rapid decision-making process versus
having some good checks and balances.

00:28:41.250 --> 00:28:46.400
Does that answer your thoughts?

00:28:46.400 --> 00:28:47.400
OK.

00:28:47.400 --> 00:28:48.430
I am going to leave that subject, unless there
are any other questions on it.

00:28:48.430 --> 00:28:50.480
Can I just bring up something?

00:28:50.480 --> 00:28:51.480
Sure.

00:28:51.480 --> 00:28:54.250
And I welcome your opinion on this, Elliot.

00:28:54.250 --> 00:29:01.000
And that is there has been a big change in
NASA recently which is affecting management.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:07.340
And that is because NASA has gone over to
what they call full cost accounting which

00:29:07.340 --> 00:29:14.670
means that during all of this time the engineering
organization maintained their engineers.

00:29:14.670 --> 00:29:15.880
That's true.

00:29:15.880 --> 00:29:22.309
They paid the salary and then they would be
assigned to projects as required.

00:29:22.309 --> 00:29:29.610
The system, as it's now working, is it's supposed
to be much more like in industry where the

00:29:29.610 --> 00:29:33.870
time of every engineer has to be billed to
a specific project.

00:29:33.870 --> 00:29:40.770
And if you don't have a project to bill your
time to, ultimately you become redundant.

00:29:40.770 --> 00:29:47.640
And so, those of you who read Aviation Week
and Space News, I hope all of you do, are

00:29:47.640 --> 00:29:52.640
aware that NASA is doing a lot of downsizing.

00:29:52.640 --> 00:29:54.820
It puts a lot of constraint on management.

00:29:54.820 --> 00:30:00.770
Now, in industry, obviously people have to
be paid for.

00:30:00.770 --> 00:30:06.780
But are there always enough projects to bill
people to?

00:30:06.780 --> 00:30:26.180
Well, there is never a situation that you
have the exact number of people.

00:30:26.180 --> 00:30:56.270
You're either short of many people, which
is now the situtation at Draper, or you don't

00:30:56.270 --> 00:31:04.390
have enough money.

00:31:04.390 --> 00:31:09.040
What you do, in a place like Draper, we have
our own money.

00:31:09.040 --> 00:31:10.040
It's called internal research.

00:31:10.040 --> 00:31:11.040
And we use some money [NOISE OBSCURES]

00:31:11.040 --> 00:31:12.040
and we keep those people.

00:31:12.040 --> 00:31:14.510
But those have to be people the company believes
can be used in the future.

00:31:14.510 --> 00:31:16.270
There is no point in keeping people that nobody
wants.

00:31:16.270 --> 00:31:19.610
Actually, the matrix system, and I talked
about it with Jerry because we are doing the

00:31:19.610 --> 00:31:22.330
evaluation, that is why I have to leave, is
really sorting the people out.

00:31:22.330 --> 00:31:23.350
Because when it was a big project, it was
a big family.

00:31:23.350 --> 00:31:24.350
The guy owned them.

00:31:24.350 --> 00:31:25.350
He knows them.

00:31:25.350 --> 00:31:26.350
That's true.

00:31:26.350 --> 00:31:27.350
Now, you work at the function organization
and we send you to work, he wants the best

00:31:27.350 --> 00:31:28.350
people for his project.

00:31:28.350 --> 00:31:29.350
He will say well, I don't want this guy.

00:31:29.350 --> 00:31:30.350
Now, if it is a mediocre guy, we will say
look, you cannot have the best.

00:31:30.350 --> 00:31:31.350
But if it is somebody who is very weak we
will say for one time, OK, maybe he didn't

00:31:31.350 --> 00:31:32.350
get along with the program so put him in another
program.

00:31:32.350 --> 00:31:33.350
But if we get the feedback, it doesn't work
there, we know there is a problem.

00:31:33.350 --> 00:31:38.030
In that way we weeded out a lot of people
that, if you have the old system, probably

00:31:38.030 --> 00:31:41.040
will stay and make us less efficient.

00:31:41.040 --> 00:31:44.480
NASA will be more efficient now, I think.

00:31:44.480 --> 00:31:46.640
I think that is true.

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:48.450
On the other hand, it causes a lot of pain.

00:31:48.450 --> 00:31:50.270
It is very difficult to let people go but
that is part of management.

00:31:50.270 --> 00:31:57.140
It's not just going to parties.

00:31:57.140 --> 00:31:59.430
[UNINTELLIGIBLE PHRASE]

00:31:59.430 --> 00:32:01.720
That's right.

00:32:01.720 --> 00:32:05.330
Yes, there is a question.

00:32:05.330 --> 00:32:11.160
I guess another angle on the "very tough to
let people go" I've noticed that it is extremely

00:32:11.160 --> 00:32:19.420
difficult from a bureaucratic standpoint to
let somebody go in government.

00:32:19.420 --> 00:32:30.770
And I'm just wondering with full cost accounting,
OK, you've decided it is time for this person

00:32:30.770 --> 00:32:33.000
to go, but there is just a lot of politics
and bureaucracy paperwork to go through to

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:34.000
get somebody out of the organization.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:35.540
There are civil service laws which have to
be complied with.

00:32:35.540 --> 00:32:36.540
It is difficult.

00:32:36.540 --> 00:32:38.780
And, I have to say, I agree with Elliot.

00:32:38.780 --> 00:32:44.490
In the long-run I think NASA will become more
efficient.

00:32:44.490 --> 00:32:48.100
Well, to answer your question, there are several
ways to let people go.

00:32:48.100 --> 00:32:50.590
One is if they've really done something bad.

00:32:50.590 --> 00:32:54.070
You have a board and you go through it and
you release them.

00:32:54.070 --> 00:33:00.900
The other is if you NASA has a downsizing,
which is called a RIF, reduce in force.

00:33:00.900 --> 00:33:04.040
Then you can arbitrarily let people go.

00:33:04.040 --> 00:33:09.040
I didn't mean to interrupt you, Jeff, but
those are two ways.

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:16.309
I will just add the third way, which NASA
is also doing, is you can offer what they

00:33:16.309 --> 00:33:17.309
call buyouts.

00:33:17.309 --> 00:33:29.000
They offer up to $25,000 if you will take
early retirement, so a lot of people do that.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:32.240
And companies, not government, have a much
easier time.

00:33:32.240 --> 00:33:37.270
I don't know how Draper is, but companies
have a much easier time letting people go

00:33:37.270 --> 00:33:39.620
than other places.

00:33:39.620 --> 00:33:42.080
But that was about all I was going to say
on management.

00:33:42.080 --> 00:33:48.820
Now I'm going to get into, you might say,
the interesting land of systems engineering

00:33:48.820 --> 00:33:51.110
and talk about systems engineering a little
bit.

00:33:51.110 --> 00:33:54.150
My charts are sort of yellow because they
go way back.

00:33:54.150 --> 00:33:59.120
It turns out systems engineering has been
studied a long time a lot.

00:33:59.120 --> 00:34:06.179
And there are many aspects of systems engineering
that some people in the room may or may not

00:34:06.179 --> 00:34:07.179
agree with.

00:34:07.179 --> 00:34:14.470
I've had time to reflect a little bit from
my days at NASA in both Apollo and Shuttle

00:34:14.470 --> 00:34:17.400
and in Space Station.

00:34:17.400 --> 00:34:25.089
And I was, as I say, Director of the Johnson
Space Center, I was Deputy Administrator,

00:34:25.089 --> 00:34:31.960
Acting Deputy Administration under Goldin
for a year, and then I taught at A&amp;M.

00:34:31.960 --> 00:34:37.669
And all that time I have had time to reflect
and I have had time to do some, you might

00:34:37.669 --> 00:34:42.221
say, research of what I thought systems engineering
was and how you explain it.

00:34:42.221 --> 00:34:43.221
I want to try to do that today.

00:34:43.221 --> 00:34:47.389
People in the room may or may not agree with
it but it is my thought process.

00:34:47.389 --> 00:34:54.659
And it turns out that much of this information
was gathered from studies done by the military,

00:34:54.659 --> 00:34:56.099
mil specs on systems engineering.

00:34:56.099 --> 00:35:00.470
They have spent an awful lot of money studying
systems engineering.

00:35:00.470 --> 00:35:05.160
And many of these charts are plagiarized,
you might say, from those studies and they

00:35:05.160 --> 00:35:07.140
look sort of like they are yellow.

00:35:07.140 --> 00:35:08.140
And they are.

00:35:08.140 --> 00:35:13.589
But let's start off with systems engineering
heritage.

00:35:13.589 --> 00:35:18.630
Systems engineering, as we pointed out, is
not new.

00:35:18.630 --> 00:35:22.579
The pyramids, you know, that was a real systems
engineering problem.

00:35:22.579 --> 00:35:25.160
I don't know how they did it but it was a
real systems engineering problem.

00:35:25.160 --> 00:35:27.099
I don't know if even Jim Nevins could do that.

00:35:27.099 --> 00:35:29.930
That was a tough job.

00:35:29.930 --> 00:35:32.680
Broadcasting service and standards.

00:35:32.680 --> 00:35:36.500
Now, most of the time when you talk to people
about systems engineering, in fact, I've done

00:35:36.500 --> 00:35:41.769
a lot of research on that, they talk about
systems engineering as operations research.

00:35:41.769 --> 00:35:44.739
Well, I don't think that can be further from
the truth of systems engineering.

00:35:44.739 --> 00:35:50.160
I think it is a tool maybe used in systems
engineering, but it is not really systems

00:35:50.160 --> 00:35:51.160
engineering.

00:35:51.160 --> 00:35:54.140
The RAND Corporation developed the systems
analysis.

00:35:54.140 --> 00:35:55.609
The Bell Labs telephone systems.

00:35:55.609 --> 00:35:57.190
That was, of course, where Joe Shea came from.

00:35:57.190 --> 00:36:01.460
Joe Shea came from the Bell Labs at the time.

00:36:01.460 --> 00:36:03.799
NASA military systems, and these are mil standards.

00:36:03.799 --> 00:36:06.109
And the Army.

00:36:06.109 --> 00:36:11.059
And then systems engineering management guide
for Belvoir Defense Systems Management College.

00:36:11.059 --> 00:36:16.849
There were a lot of studies done for systems
engineering.

00:36:16.849 --> 00:36:22.220
And we, in Apollo, were trying to do systems
engineering in the 1960s for Apollo, is when

00:36:22.220 --> 00:36:24.000
we tried to start to do it.

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:43.859
By the way, these charts are not on the Web
but I will give these to Jeff and they will

00:36:43.859 --> 00:36:44.859
be on the Web.

00:36:44.859 --> 00:36:52.039
Trans-highlighting the need for increased
systems engineering, there is a need to manage

00:36:52.039 --> 00:36:58.890
the total picture in the area of increasing
system size and cost, but even a small project

00:36:58.890 --> 00:37:01.579
has systems engineering.

00:37:01.579 --> 00:37:10.390
If you can think of how you design a bicycle,
how you design an automobile, I mean these

00:37:10.390 --> 00:37:12.369
are very complex problems.

00:37:12.369 --> 00:37:13.369
They are not simple.

00:37:13.369 --> 00:37:17.470
They are really systems engineering problems.

00:37:17.470 --> 00:37:25.529
But the increasing technological growth and
specialization, increasing systems complexity,

00:37:25.529 --> 00:37:29.910
you know, the PC is a fantastic systems engineering
problem.

00:37:29.910 --> 00:37:36.999
And I guess Bill Gates saw the need for a
true systems engineering job and made a lot

00:37:36.999 --> 00:37:42.420
of money on it in terms of what he did understanding
systems engineering.

00:37:42.420 --> 00:37:46.460
Increasing sensitivity to environmental factors
and increasing costs of life cycle.

00:37:46.460 --> 00:37:52.410
All those things make the trend in systems
engineering important.

00:37:52.410 --> 00:38:03.410
And, as I look at your reports, wherever you
got it, I think you have a pretty good knowledge

00:38:03.410 --> 00:38:06.681
of what systems engineering is.

00:38:06.681 --> 00:38:11.270
So, I am not sure this lecture is going to
help you that much because I think you do

00:38:11.270 --> 00:38:13.710
look at it from a systems engineering standpoint.

00:38:13.710 --> 00:38:16.289
By the way, my last topic is going to be cost
analysis.

00:38:16.289 --> 00:38:20.819
I'm sure you're waiting to hear that because
cost analysis is very hard for you to come

00:38:20.819 --> 00:38:21.819
to grips with.

00:38:21.819 --> 00:38:27.799
And I am going to talk a little bit about
how you would go about doing a cost analysis

00:38:27.799 --> 00:38:30.549
which may not dot all the Is and cross all
the Ts for you.

00:38:30.549 --> 00:38:32.009
But I am going to try to do that.

00:38:32.009 --> 00:38:36.769
We're going to take a break at about 11:00
and then I will have some time to go through

00:38:36.769 --> 00:38:37.769
cost analysis.

00:38:37.769 --> 00:38:39.140
Well, what is systems engineering?

00:38:39.140 --> 00:38:40.140
I don't know.

00:38:40.140 --> 00:38:45.150
You may not agree with this, but systems engineering
is the application of scientific and engineering

00:38:45.150 --> 00:38:53.489
to transfer an operational need into a description
of system performance parameters and of systems

00:38:53.489 --> 00:38:56.960
configuration through an iterative process.

00:38:56.960 --> 00:38:58.809
Now, let me give you a needs statement.

00:38:58.809 --> 00:39:05.260
When President Kennedy said we are going to
send men to the Moon and return them safety

00:39:05.260 --> 00:39:08.289
within a decade that is a perfect needs statement.

00:39:08.289 --> 00:39:15.039
It doesn't tell you how to do it, he didn't
put a cost constraint on it, he did put a

00:39:15.039 --> 00:39:19.830
time constraint on it, and he told you what
you had to do but didn't tell you anything

00:39:19.830 --> 00:39:21.539
about how to do it.

00:39:21.539 --> 00:39:24.460
That is a very good needs statement.

00:39:24.460 --> 00:39:31.589
I don't know if he did that for that reason,
but he gave the public and NASA a very good

00:39:31.589 --> 00:39:32.890
needs statement.

00:39:32.890 --> 00:39:38.619
Now, our job was to transform an operational
need into a description of system performance

00:39:38.619 --> 00:39:41.319
parameters and the system configuration through
an iterative process.

00:39:41.319 --> 00:39:44.460
And that is an exercise left to the student.

00:39:44.460 --> 00:39:48.009
That is not easy to do, but that is really
what you need to do.

00:39:48.009 --> 00:39:52.270
Now, to integrate technical parameters and
insure capability of all interfaces, that

00:39:52.270 --> 00:39:53.999
is what I talked about.

00:39:53.999 --> 00:39:56.069
You talked about physical, functional and
program interfaces.

00:39:56.069 --> 00:40:00.999
They call them different things but basically
interfaces become a very important part of

00:40:00.999 --> 00:40:03.160
the systems engineering process.

00:40:03.160 --> 00:40:10.170
And the other factors into the total engineering
are to meet cost, schedule and technical performance.

00:40:10.170 --> 00:40:11.309
What is that?

00:40:11.309 --> 00:40:13.759
I think Professor Hoffman talked about that.

00:40:13.759 --> 00:40:15.769
That is the three-legged stool.

00:40:15.769 --> 00:40:18.359
It is schedule, performance and cost.

00:40:18.359 --> 00:40:21.349
It is a continuous tradeoff because you are
going to have a criteria.

00:40:21.349 --> 00:40:27.770
Whereas, President Kennedy didn't give us
a cost, he did give us a schedule and, to

00:40:27.770 --> 00:40:28.910
a certain extent, performance.

00:40:28.910 --> 00:40:31.089
But he didn't give us a cost.

00:40:31.089 --> 00:40:35.109
Now, as it turns out, cost always becomes
a factor.

00:40:35.109 --> 00:40:36.720
It always becomes a factor.

00:40:36.720 --> 00:40:44.950
But those were the things that really comprised,
you might say, in simple-minded terms systems

00:40:44.950 --> 00:40:45.980
engineering.

00:40:45.980 --> 00:40:48.279
I cannot emphasize those enough.

00:40:48.279 --> 00:40:53.579
Now, I don't know if that is how you visualize
systems engineering or how everybody in the

00:40:53.579 --> 00:40:59.460
room visualizes systems engineering but that
and the design process is really what systems

00:40:59.460 --> 00:41:00.940
engineering and design is all about.

00:41:00.940 --> 00:41:07.660
Now, whether we utilize that always in design
of our projects I cannot say.

00:41:07.660 --> 00:41:13.119
I think we could have done a better upfront
job in systems engineering on the Shuttle.

00:41:13.119 --> 00:41:14.609
I really think we could have.

00:41:14.609 --> 00:41:19.410
I see things we could have done differently
on the Shuttle today if we really practiced

00:41:19.410 --> 00:41:20.869
a true systems engineering process.

00:41:20.869 --> 00:41:26.690
It is very difficult to do because you can
stay in this systems engineering loop a long

00:41:26.690 --> 00:41:29.270
time and not get anything done.

00:41:29.270 --> 00:41:36.390
There is an old adage, if you never get out
of this loop, you could do something, do something

00:41:36.390 --> 00:41:41.200
and do something and never get anything done,
so you've got to be very careful with that.

00:41:41.200 --> 00:41:44.509
What is the role of systems engineering?

00:41:44.509 --> 00:41:51.549
Technical customer interface requirements
definition.

00:41:51.549 --> 00:41:56.880
Requirements definition sound very, very simple,
but requirements definition is probably one

00:41:56.880 --> 00:42:00.591
of the hardest things you have to do, is to
find out what the true requirements are.

00:42:00.591 --> 00:42:05.760
And, unfortunately, requirements do change
as a function of time as you go through the

00:42:05.760 --> 00:42:07.150
phase of the program.

00:42:07.150 --> 00:42:13.940
But requirements definition is very, very
difficult to do and very important to come

00:42:13.940 --> 00:42:14.940
to grips with.

00:42:14.940 --> 00:42:21.720
As JR Thompson talked to you, I don't know
if you recall JR's review of the Shuttle main

00:42:21.720 --> 00:42:22.720
engine, SSME.

00:42:22.720 --> 00:42:30.479
He said had they widened the throat a little
bit they would have reduced the complexity

00:42:30.479 --> 00:42:35.299
of the design and development of the main
engine.

00:42:35.299 --> 00:42:38.670
Made it much more reliable but you would give
up some performance.

00:42:38.670 --> 00:42:42.339
Now, why didn't we do that?

00:42:42.339 --> 00:42:46.410
Because there was a requirement to advance
technology.

00:42:46.410 --> 00:42:50.519
And I think JR made a very, very important
point there that those are things you need

00:42:50.519 --> 00:42:52.069
to look at early in the program.

00:42:52.069 --> 00:42:55.979
So, requirements definition are very important,
extremely important.

00:42:55.979 --> 00:42:59.401
And it is very difficult to get to the bottom
of it.

00:42:59.401 --> 00:43:04.579
Requirements definition is a task in itself.

00:43:04.579 --> 00:43:09.089
And then, of course, there is a requirements
management analysis and flow down audit.

00:43:09.089 --> 00:43:11.470
And then, again, you get interface management.

00:43:11.470 --> 00:43:15.289
Risk management is becoming a big item today.

00:43:15.289 --> 00:43:19.369
You heard Bob Siemens talk, and I didn't mention
Bob Siemens.

00:43:19.369 --> 00:43:27.369
He is another very, very important man in
this whole era of Apollo and down to Shuttle.

00:43:27.369 --> 00:43:31.420
His role cannot be stated too highly.

00:43:31.420 --> 00:43:34.489
He did a fantastic job.

00:43:34.489 --> 00:43:37.940
His risk management was very interesting.

00:43:37.940 --> 00:43:40.210
I heard him talk not too long ago.

00:43:40.210 --> 00:43:45.869
And he said that the risk management in terms
of cost and in terms of human life for the

00:43:45.869 --> 00:43:52.589
Apollo program was accepted, not only by the
executive branch, the legislative branch but

00:43:52.589 --> 00:43:53.920
the public.

00:43:53.920 --> 00:43:55.400
So, risk management needs to be accepted.

00:43:55.400 --> 00:43:58.420
And that is one thing that is very, very important.

00:43:58.420 --> 00:44:05.950
Understand what the risk management is in
terms of life, in terms of cost and in terms

00:44:05.950 --> 00:44:07.069
of what it is going to do for you.

00:44:07.069 --> 00:44:08.859
So, risk management is very important.

00:44:08.859 --> 00:44:13.309
And it is the function of the systems engineer
to bring that to bear.

00:44:13.309 --> 00:44:17.539
Performance management, design process, so
forth and so on.

00:44:17.539 --> 00:44:18.989
Technology need identifier.

00:44:18.989 --> 00:44:28.539
I had the reputation of not wanting to advance
technology mainly because of budget constraints

00:44:28.539 --> 00:44:30.570
and I wanted to go with given technology.

00:44:30.570 --> 00:44:33.130
Is that right?

00:44:33.130 --> 00:44:38.410
I don't know if that is right or not, but
the point being is that technology can drive

00:44:38.410 --> 00:44:39.410
a program.

00:44:39.410 --> 00:44:44.520
The fact that you have to develop the technology
can drive the program.

00:44:44.520 --> 00:44:50.680
These are what the role of a systems engineering
needs to do to figure out how they are going

00:44:50.680 --> 00:44:59.849
to handle technology, if they are going to
advance technology or not.

00:44:59.849 --> 00:45:03.681
What is a system?

00:45:03.681 --> 00:45:11.390
A system is a complete solution to a defined
need in its full environment over the prescribed

00:45:11.390 --> 00:45:12.390
life.

00:45:12.390 --> 00:45:18.259
The system includes hardware, software, documentation,
human resources, nonhuman resources, esoteric

00:45:18.259 --> 00:45:19.259
factors.

00:45:19.259 --> 00:45:21.589
It includes almost everything you can think
about.

00:45:21.589 --> 00:45:25.259
Software turns out to be a big driver today.

00:45:25.259 --> 00:45:28.700
Software in the system turns out to be one
of the largest drivers.

00:45:28.700 --> 00:45:34.519
Some of you asked me, and I hope it helped,
what was the cost of the Shuttle Guidance

00:45:34.519 --> 00:45:36.039
and Navigation System.

00:45:36.039 --> 00:45:40.089
I don't know who asked me for that.

00:45:40.089 --> 00:45:41.609
Somebody asked me.

00:45:41.609 --> 00:45:46.140
Was that helpful to you, the number we gave
you?

00:45:46.140 --> 00:45:47.290
The Shuttle.

00:45:47.290 --> 00:45:50.210
They wanted to know the Shuttle.

00:45:50.210 --> 00:45:55.681
But the fact is it didn't separate the cost
of the software and the hardware.

00:45:55.681 --> 00:46:02.489
And the hardware came on pretty much on cost
but the software was a lot higher.

00:46:02.489 --> 00:46:06.079
It was exponentially growing.

00:46:06.079 --> 00:46:08.720
Software turns out to be, I don't know, Jerry,
do you want to say a word on software?

00:46:08.720 --> 00:46:22.150
Well, the problems of software were the issues
of validation, verifying tests and retests.

00:46:22.150 --> 00:46:34.390
And then every once in a while somebody would
come along and say well, but we really ought

00:46:34.390 --> 00:46:37.559
to add this.

00:46:37.559 --> 00:46:42.650
And adding on was a killer.

00:46:42.650 --> 00:46:56.380
Well, as Bill Tenel used to say, it is sort
of the garbage dump for things you couldn't

00:46:56.380 --> 00:46:58.359
do in the hardware.

00:46:58.359 --> 00:47:05.849
The number that I remember is at some point,
when you wanted to change one line of code,

00:47:05.849 --> 00:47:06.849
IBM wanted $1 million.

00:47:06.849 --> 00:47:08.349
Each time for one line of code because they
had to change the whole software, so that

00:47:08.349 --> 00:47:09.369
is why they have the software control mode
[NOISE OBSCURES].

00:47:09.369 --> 00:47:10.369
That's right.

00:47:10.369 --> 00:47:11.569
I remember when I retired, Dave Leestma, who
was head of the Astronaut Office at the time,

00:47:11.569 --> 00:47:13.069
said that he thought he could get a change
through.

00:47:13.069 --> 00:47:14.069
I forgot.

00:47:14.069 --> 00:47:15.069
It was something to do with return to launch
site.

00:47:15.069 --> 00:47:18.230
I don't remember what it was but it was some
kind of program he wanted to put in.

00:47:18.230 --> 00:47:21.450
He talked to everybody and they all approved
it, and it came to me and I turned it down.

00:47:21.450 --> 00:47:24.670
And he said at my retirement party, now Aaron
is leaving, maybe we can get it approved.

00:47:24.670 --> 00:47:25.740
But software changes do increase the cost
of the program.

00:47:25.740 --> 00:47:29.869
A simple system example.

00:47:29.869 --> 00:47:30.869
Space Shuttle.

00:47:30.869 --> 00:47:31.869
Your house.

00:47:31.869 --> 00:47:32.869
Electronic calculator.

00:47:32.869 --> 00:47:33.869
Freeway.

00:47:33.869 --> 00:47:34.869
The Golden Gate Bridge.

00:47:34.869 --> 00:47:35.869
Rapid transit.

00:47:35.869 --> 00:47:36.869
Computers.

00:47:36.869 --> 00:47:40.619
A system really involves everything.

00:47:40.619 --> 00:47:44.819
Almost everything you can think of is a system.

00:47:44.819 --> 00:47:49.150
The other thing that is interesting is this
chart right here.

00:47:49.150 --> 00:47:53.559
You may have seen this charge before, you've
seen it different ways, but the importance

00:47:53.559 --> 00:47:57.509
of systems engineering, the systems engineering
is doing the right thing right.

00:47:57.509 --> 00:48:03.479
As system increase in complexity and value,
early system decisions become increasingly

00:48:03.479 --> 00:48:04.479
important.

00:48:04.479 --> 00:48:12.380
It shows that actually in the impact of program
funding, when 10% of the program funding is

00:48:12.380 --> 00:48:17.410
accomplished you have actually committed 90%
of your dollars, systems engineering systems

00:48:17.410 --> 00:48:24.239
have actually committed 90% of your dollars,
so that means early decision-making on systems

00:48:24.239 --> 00:48:25.239
engineering.

00:48:25.239 --> 00:48:30.009
And whether you were going to make the engine
throat wide or not actually impacts the program

00:48:30.009 --> 00:48:31.009
very heavily earlier.

00:48:31.009 --> 00:48:36.200
That is why systems engineering is so important.

00:48:36.200 --> 00:48:48.069
Systems engineering is requirements in solution
management.

00:48:48.069 --> 00:48:54.069
Understanding analysis, allocations, so forth
and so on, which really affect performance,

00:48:54.069 --> 00:48:55.069
cost and schedule.

00:48:55.069 --> 00:48:58.489
And there is the three-legged stool again.

00:48:58.489 --> 00:49:03.690
This really says that if you remember certain
parameters, the continued tradeoff between

00:49:03.690 --> 00:49:10.559
cost, schedule and performance is really one
of the most important things you can understand

00:49:10.559 --> 00:49:26.710
that is really a systems engineering job.

00:49:26.710 --> 00:49:34.290
One thing I would like to talk about is the
attributes of a systems engineering.

00:49:34.290 --> 00:49:36.569
Systems engineers are very hard to come by.

00:49:36.569 --> 00:49:43.119
They really are very hard to come by, and
it is almost hard to tell you how to become

00:49:43.119 --> 00:49:44.119
one.

00:49:44.119 --> 00:49:49.190
I mean there are courses you can take, but
one thing I would suggest you do, if you really

00:49:49.190 --> 00:49:55.640
want to be a systems engineer is you specialize
in one technical area.

00:49:55.640 --> 00:50:02.930
Whether it be structures, whether it be thermodynamics,
heat transfer, guidance and control, control

00:50:02.930 --> 00:50:05.180
systems, specialize in one area.

00:50:05.180 --> 00:50:07.109
That is the first step.

00:50:07.109 --> 00:50:14.910
You need to be competent and show your competency
in one area, but then you need to broaden

00:50:14.910 --> 00:50:20.369
out a little bit and look at how people actually
operate.

00:50:20.369 --> 00:50:24.739
Good judgment of technical competence in others.

00:50:24.739 --> 00:50:28.029
Ability to build trust of team customer management.

00:50:28.029 --> 00:50:33.359
And this is what this course is about, to
work as a team and to have relationships with

00:50:33.359 --> 00:50:34.359
each other.

00:50:34.359 --> 00:50:41.420
I don't know if it was true at MIT, but many
years ago in universities it was very bad

00:50:41.420 --> 00:50:44.719
to work as a team because you tended to rely
on each other.

00:50:44.719 --> 00:50:50.499
And they wanted to have independent research,
independent development, so students were

00:50:50.499 --> 00:50:52.822
not really encouraged to work as teams.

00:50:52.822 --> 00:50:53.822
I don't know if that is true at MIT but it
was certainly true at some universities I

00:50:53.822 --> 00:50:54.822
knew.

00:50:54.822 --> 00:50:55.822
I don't know.

00:50:55.822 --> 00:50:56.822
Was it true?

00:50:56.822 --> 00:50:57.822
Well, we've gone through a major shift.

00:50:57.822 --> 00:50:58.822
And I think the rest of the country is as
well from individual to team effort.

00:50:58.822 --> 00:50:59.822
Yeah, team effort.

00:50:59.822 --> 00:51:00.822
Particularly in engineering.

00:51:00.822 --> 00:51:01.822
That's right.

00:51:01.822 --> 00:51:02.822
When I first went to A&amp;M, they thought it
was terrible.

00:51:02.822 --> 00:51:03.822
Some of the professors thought it was terrible
working as teams.

00:51:03.822 --> 00:51:04.822
The difficult that all the top universities
have is you guys are all admitted on the basis

00:51:04.822 --> 00:51:05.822
of your high school or I guess in graduate
school your college grads, so those are individual

00:51:05.822 --> 00:51:06.822
efforts that got you here.

00:51:06.822 --> 00:51:07.822
Now we're saying put the emphasis on team
activity.

00:51:07.822 --> 00:51:08.822
The Japanese have traditionally done that
far better than we have.

00:51:08.822 --> 00:51:09.822
That's right.

00:51:09.822 --> 00:51:10.822
I just wanted to strengthen what you said
because a lot of people think that a systems

00:51:10.822 --> 00:51:11.822
engineer should be a "Jack of all trades"
and should know a little bit about everything.

00:51:11.822 --> 00:51:12.822
Absolutely not true.

00:51:12.822 --> 00:51:15.109
You have to be very good in one specific area,
and that is your baseline.

00:51:15.109 --> 00:51:16.109
That's right.

00:51:16.109 --> 00:51:24.809
The most difficult thing in engineering as
a manager is to make a decision when the guy

00:51:24.809 --> 00:51:51.749
who comes to you knows about the subject more
than you because he is the expert.

00:51:51.749 --> 00:52:01.589
And the only way you can do it is by knowing
how an expert behaves.

00:52:01.589 --> 00:52:08.910
And, in your area of expertise, you can make
that judgment.

00:52:08.910 --> 00:52:17.489
Some people are confused on this, but I think
that I 100% agree with you.

00:52:17.489 --> 00:52:25.190
You have to be an expert in one field, otherwise
it won't work.

00:52:25.190 --> 00:52:35.489
I should say there have been a lot of discussions
among the faculty in the Aero-Astro Department

00:52:35.489 --> 00:52:42.619
and perhaps in other departments as well as
to when systems engineering should be taught.

00:52:42.619 --> 00:52:46.279
Should it be taught at the undergraduate level?

00:52:46.279 --> 00:52:55.739
And right now the guiding philosophy in the
Aero-Astro Department is to devote undergraduate

00:52:55.739 --> 00:53:03.509
time really to building up expertise in the
individual subject matter, as Elliot said.

00:53:03.509 --> 00:53:10.980
The idea being that wait until you really
have a good grounding as an engineer in one

00:53:10.980 --> 00:53:18.710
or more specific subjects, and then, at the
graduate level, that is time enough to actually

00:53:18.710 --> 00:53:23.690
look at systems engineering as a discipline
so that you can draw on the expertise that

00:53:23.690 --> 00:53:24.690
you have built up.

00:53:24.690 --> 00:53:29.219
That is not a universally held decision.

00:53:29.219 --> 00:53:36.380
And there are people who make a good pedagogical
case that you can actually start teaching

00:53:36.380 --> 00:53:41.079
principles of systems engineering right from
the freshman level.

00:53:41.079 --> 00:53:50.269
And, in the whole CDIO philosophy that our
department tries to follow, we try to develop

00:53:50.269 --> 00:53:55.529
these principles which we think will then
be useful as you get into more technical aspects

00:53:55.529 --> 00:53:57.079
of systems engineering levels.

00:53:57.079 --> 00:54:04.900
We always try to balance the technical expertise
with the systems level thinking.

00:54:04.900 --> 00:54:06.259
Yes, Jerry.

00:54:06.259 --> 00:54:20.130
I would like to point out that in the organizing
teams, a key important feature of that is

00:54:20.130 --> 00:54:22.269
to have that systems engineer who is organizing
the team and setting up the meetings to know

00:54:22.269 --> 00:54:23.269
why and who should be attending.

00:54:23.269 --> 00:54:27.970
I attended a number of Space Station meetings
when I had these product teams where every

00:54:27.970 --> 00:54:30.140
company in the world was there.

00:54:30.140 --> 00:54:31.950
And you had 50 people sitting around and there
were only four who were real contributors,

00:54:31.950 --> 00:54:32.950
and the others I could swear were falling
asleep.

00:54:32.950 --> 00:54:44.430
You fundamentally have to have good management
in team setups.

00:54:44.430 --> 00:54:46.609
Well, you're absolutely right.

00:54:46.609 --> 00:54:51.829
Of course, one of the problems with Space
Station, in all honesty, if you had tried

00:54:51.829 --> 00:54:56.690
to devise a management system that was complex
the Space Station system would have won because

00:54:56.690 --> 00:54:57.950
it is probably the most complex management
system.

00:54:57.950 --> 00:54:59.269
In fact, I tried to explain it to the Bob
Gilruth one time, who is another man I should

00:54:59.269 --> 00:55:00.269
have mentioned.

00:55:00.269 --> 00:55:03.029
He was the Director of the Johnson Space Center.

00:55:03.029 --> 00:55:07.910
And he came to see me and his eyes just rolled
back in his head.

00:55:07.910 --> 00:55:12.089
He couldn't figure out what I was talking
about.

00:55:12.089 --> 00:55:13.090
So, you're right.

00:55:13.090 --> 00:55:16.779
But, you know, the other person that agrees
with you, Elliot, is Chris Kraft.

00:55:16.779 --> 00:55:24.549
Chris Kraft feels very strongly about becoming
an expert in one field before you tackle something.

00:55:24.549 --> 00:55:25.549
Self-motivated.

00:55:25.549 --> 00:55:26.599
Able to motivate others.

00:55:26.599 --> 00:55:34.239
In matrix management, that becomes a good
systems engineer, if you're able to motivate

00:55:34.239 --> 00:55:35.239
others.

00:55:35.239 --> 00:55:36.239
Methodical.

00:55:36.239 --> 00:55:37.239
Analytical.

00:55:37.239 --> 00:55:38.239
Intuitive.

00:55:38.239 --> 00:55:39.239
Questioning.

00:55:39.239 --> 00:55:40.239
Open-minded.

00:55:40.239 --> 00:55:41.569
I think that is one of the key points, being
open-minded.

00:55:41.569 --> 00:55:51.479
If you make a mistake be ready to accept the
mistake and correct it and make a change to

00:55:51.479 --> 00:55:52.479
it.

00:55:52.479 --> 00:55:53.950
That is very important in systems engineering,
especially if you have to make some important

00:55:53.950 --> 00:55:54.950
decisions.

00:55:54.950 --> 00:55:55.950
Confident.

00:55:55.950 --> 00:55:56.950
A good communicator.

00:55:56.950 --> 00:55:58.069
High level of integrity.

00:55:58.069 --> 00:56:04.079
So, that is really some of my background on
systems engineering.

00:56:04.079 --> 00:56:10.499
Now, let's talk a little bit about more how
you go about doing it.

00:56:10.499 --> 00:56:12.180
Thank you, Elliot.

00:56:12.180 --> 00:56:35.319
A system is generally considered a conglomeration
of objects that perform a specific function.

00:56:35.319 --> 00:56:36.339
And you can think of those.

00:56:36.339 --> 00:56:40.979
I mean you can think of all those in the laptop
computers you have, many things like that

00:56:40.979 --> 00:56:43.109
which we talked about.

00:56:43.109 --> 00:56:45.400
And I mentioned this before.

00:56:45.400 --> 00:56:47.809
This is what I say.

00:56:47.809 --> 00:56:51.599
It is a postulate or whatever you want to
call it.

00:56:51.599 --> 00:56:57.219
What is important for the whole system is
nearly identical to what would be the best

00:56:57.219 --> 00:57:00.609
in the long-run for each of its components.

00:57:00.609 --> 00:57:04.190
However, what is best for each individual
constituent may not be the best for the whole

00:57:04.190 --> 00:57:05.190
system.

00:57:05.190 --> 00:57:08.480
And so that really is something you need to
keep in mind.

00:57:08.480 --> 00:57:12.019
That is really the postulate of systems engineering.

00:57:12.019 --> 00:57:22.660
It may be the right thing for the system but
it may not be the right thing for the total

00:57:22.660 --> 00:57:23.789
configuration.

00:57:23.789 --> 00:57:32.190
And the systems engineering process is the
customer/user need analysis, mission requirements,

00:57:32.190 --> 00:57:36.180
functional analysis, system concept, development,
tradeoffs, design.

00:57:36.180 --> 00:57:42.259
Now, this is systems engineering as it pertains
to design.

00:57:42.259 --> 00:57:46.849
Now, there is systems engineering as it pertains
to operations, but this is systems engineering

00:57:46.849 --> 00:57:48.480
as it pertains to design.

00:57:48.480 --> 00:57:51.989
Design optimization, requirements flow down,
telecommunication, design insurance, verification

00:57:51.989 --> 00:57:55.400
audit and then you go through this iteration
process.

00:57:55.400 --> 00:57:58.890
In fact, this is what you do in your mind.

00:57:58.890 --> 00:57:59.979
I am sure you do that.

00:57:59.979 --> 00:58:03.579
When I taught this, when I spoke about this
to several professors, my friends at Texas

00:58:03.579 --> 00:58:06.719
A&amp;M, they say well, there is nothing in this.

00:58:06.719 --> 00:58:10.509
They said it is all commonsense.

00:58:10.509 --> 00:58:13.859
And, to a greater extent, it is commonsense.

00:58:13.859 --> 00:58:17.029
But the problem is do you really practice
it?

00:58:17.029 --> 00:58:21.150
Do you really have a process in place and
do you really practice it?

00:58:21.150 --> 00:58:25.979
And we find that we don't really practice
it too well.

00:58:25.979 --> 00:58:28.239
And we say this over and over again.

00:58:28.239 --> 00:58:35.849
But the three factors of systems engineering
will be the cost, schedule and performance.

00:58:35.849 --> 00:58:39.499
And that is the famous three-legged stool
that we talked about many times.

00:58:39.499 --> 00:58:41.969
But that really is the essence.

00:58:41.969 --> 00:58:47.079
And, you as an engineer going to work and
getting paid, that is what you're going to

00:58:47.079 --> 00:58:50.739
be paid for, getting a product out the door
that essentially meets the cost schedule and

00:58:50.739 --> 00:58:51.739
performance.

00:58:51.739 --> 00:58:52.739
You look quizzical.

00:58:52.739 --> 00:58:53.739
Excuse me.

00:58:53.739 --> 00:58:54.739
No, go ahead.

00:58:54.739 --> 00:58:55.739
The statistic that you gave.

00:58:55.739 --> 00:58:56.739
After 10% of the project funding then you
have 90% of your requirements defined, do

00:58:56.739 --> 00:59:18.170
you think that function there might change
today now that we have faster prototyping

00:59:18.170 --> 00:59:20.049
tools?

00:59:20.049 --> 00:59:21.339
It could change, yes.

00:59:21.339 --> 00:59:23.940
This was done some time ago.

00:59:23.940 --> 00:59:24.940
Technology is changing.

00:59:24.940 --> 00:59:25.940
Rapid prototype is changing.

00:59:25.940 --> 00:59:28.640
CAD design.

00:59:28.640 --> 00:59:31.219
A lot of things are changing.

00:59:31.219 --> 00:59:42.130
It might be not quite as dramatic, you might
say, but it is still going to be there.

00:59:42.130 --> 00:59:46.789
A lot of your system engineering decisions
are going to affect your end product very

00:59:46.789 --> 00:59:48.299
early in the game.

00:59:48.299 --> 00:59:58.089
And one reason why that 90% gets locked in
is because of the difficulty of making changes

00:59:58.089 --> 00:59:59.950
once you've got all the plans drawn.

00:59:59.950 --> 01:00:00.950
That's right.

01:00:00.950 --> 01:00:07.900
And so, to the extent that CAD systems make
it easier to change drawings and propagate

01:00:07.900 --> 01:00:14.579
changes throughout the system, it may be that
making certain changes are less expensive

01:00:14.579 --> 01:00:15.579
than they might have been.

01:00:15.579 --> 01:00:27.029
As Jerry said about software, you start changing
your software around, you've got to do re-verification

01:00:27.029 --> 01:00:28.029
and so on.

01:00:28.029 --> 01:00:38.999
Certainly, to the degree that modern techniques
might make things more flexible, that number

01:00:38.999 --> 01:00:40.869
might get pushed down a little bit.

01:00:40.869 --> 01:00:49.670
But generally, once you've gone through preliminary
design review, you have basically set the

01:00:49.670 --> 01:00:56.069
parameters of your project and things have
a momentum and it really does get harder to

01:00:56.069 --> 01:00:57.069
change.

01:00:57.069 --> 01:01:01.369
And, of course, once you've gotten to the
critical design review -- That's right.

01:01:01.369 --> 01:01:05.680
At that point you're starting to cut metal.

01:01:05.680 --> 01:01:12.799
And then, once you've actually started to
build something, the price of changes goes

01:01:12.799 --> 01:01:14.349
up astronomically.

01:01:14.349 --> 01:01:22.130
When we did the Apollo Program we started
in '61.

01:01:22.130 --> 01:01:32.059
It is my guess that by '64, and not too far
into '64, I remember June of '64 we had the

01:01:32.059 --> 01:01:33.319
implementation meetings with Apollo.

01:01:33.319 --> 01:01:35.920
By that time all the hardware definition was
in place.

01:01:35.920 --> 01:01:36.920
That's right.

01:01:36.920 --> 01:01:37.999
The program went on after that.

01:01:37.999 --> 01:01:45.619
And the only thing that kept growing or changing
was software, but the basic hardware picture

01:01:45.619 --> 01:01:49.750
was pretty much the nail was in, in 1964,
three years into the program.

01:01:49.750 --> 01:01:53.680
Well, as Jeff said, once you start cutting
chips and start cutting hardware it is pretty

01:01:53.680 --> 01:01:55.660
hard to make changes.

01:01:55.660 --> 01:02:00.099
If I could clarify.

01:02:00.099 --> 01:02:05.380
What exactly is it that is being locked in?

01:02:05.380 --> 01:02:06.530
Well, usually your requirements.

01:02:06.530 --> 01:02:11.450
Primarily what your requirements are is the
big driver.

01:02:11.450 --> 01:02:18.180
And then, once your requirements are defined,
you can actually start your iterative process

01:02:18.180 --> 01:02:20.109
of design.

01:02:20.109 --> 01:02:26.329
Once you get your functional performance requirements
defined, you then start your design iteration

01:02:26.329 --> 01:02:31.490
and you start locking into things and, pretty
quick, you start cutting hardware and software.

01:02:31.490 --> 01:02:36.209
Hopefully you have gotten a sense, from all
of the lectures on the subsystems of the Shuttle,

01:02:36.209 --> 01:02:40.720
the degree to which they interact with one
another.

01:02:40.720 --> 01:02:42.970
That's a good point.

01:02:42.970 --> 01:02:52.690
I mean imagine if halfway down the road there
had been a major change to the thermal protection

01:02:52.690 --> 01:02:56.599
system which had bumped the weight up by,
say, 20%.

01:02:56.599 --> 01:03:02.420
Imagine the ripples that that would have affected.

01:03:02.420 --> 01:03:10.140
Or, if somebody wanted to change the requirements
for cross-range, after you had done the basic

01:03:10.140 --> 01:03:11.140
design of the system.

01:03:11.140 --> 01:03:14.829
Let me give you a very real example in that.

01:03:14.829 --> 01:03:15.979
We had the wing basically designed.

01:03:15.979 --> 01:03:21.670
And you know that the landing gear comes up
in the wing box.

01:03:21.670 --> 01:03:28.920
Well, we came to the conclusion that if you
blew one tire on touchdown you could blow

01:03:28.920 --> 01:03:30.499
all the tires.

01:03:30.499 --> 01:03:35.229
And so, what they wanted to do is increase
the number of tires that went into the wheel

01:03:35.229 --> 01:03:36.229
well.

01:03:36.229 --> 01:03:37.780
And that was pretty late in the program.

01:03:37.780 --> 01:03:43.550
I mean we had already decided, from the systems
engineering point of view, we were going to

01:03:43.550 --> 01:03:47.499
have the number of wheels we had and go up
into the wheel well.

01:03:47.499 --> 01:03:53.300
But then came along a study that showed well,
if you blew one tire you're liable to lose

01:03:53.300 --> 01:03:54.509
the vehicle on touchdown.

01:03:54.509 --> 01:03:59.999
They wanted to go put more tires into that
wheel well.

01:03:59.999 --> 01:04:01.249
Well, can you imagine what that would do?

01:04:01.249 --> 01:04:06.630
That would be redesigning the whole wing when
the wing was built, so we lived with that.

01:04:06.630 --> 01:04:12.219
We lived with that with some risk, but you
didn't make the change to it.

01:04:12.219 --> 01:04:16.329
That's the type of thing that gets into it.

01:04:16.329 --> 01:04:20.839
And I'm sure there are a number of items I
could talk about that would cause that problem

01:04:20.839 --> 01:04:22.480
to occur.

01:04:22.480 --> 01:04:34.640
Sometimes if you come up with a problem that
really would be fatal, you've got to change

01:04:34.640 --> 01:04:35.640
it.

01:04:35.640 --> 01:04:36.640
You've got to stop, yeah.

01:04:36.640 --> 01:04:40.749
And one of the examples being the O ring seal
on the solid booster.

01:04:40.749 --> 01:04:45.869
In retrospect, people have said we should
have changed that at the beginning.

01:04:45.869 --> 01:04:49.089
Now, who knows?

01:04:49.089 --> 01:04:53.569
If on one of the Shuttle flights a tire had
blown and we had lost the entire vehicle,

01:04:53.569 --> 01:04:56.160
there would have been an accident investigation
board.

01:04:56.160 --> 01:05:01.200
And they would have gone back and said we
were flying with an untenable system.

01:05:01.200 --> 01:05:02.690
And we should have made that change.

01:05:02.690 --> 01:05:11.739
And that is where the engineer who has become
a manager is really faced with a tough potentially

01:05:11.739 --> 01:05:14.010
life or death decision.

01:05:14.010 --> 01:05:22.329
And there is always an element of risk, but
if you try to take out all the elements of

01:05:22.329 --> 01:05:24.440
risk you will never fly.

01:05:24.440 --> 01:05:25.440
Well, that's absolutely right.

01:05:25.440 --> 01:05:28.920
And so how do you make that judgment?

01:05:28.920 --> 01:05:33.949
As I said, that is why they pay you such a
big salary.

01:05:33.949 --> 01:05:37.749
Well, the interesting part about that is after
the Challenger accident my deputy, who became

01:05:37.749 --> 01:05:41.020
a very good friend of yours, Paul Whites,
who was an astronaut, a Navy fighter pilot.

01:05:41.020 --> 01:05:49.069
And our job was to get the Shuttle flying
again after the Challenger accident.

01:05:49.069 --> 01:05:53.760
I thought I brought it with me.

01:05:53.760 --> 01:06:01.459
We found this picture of a ship on a very
ominous sea.

01:06:01.459 --> 01:06:06.019
It said a ship in the harbor is safe, but
that is not what ships are built for.

01:06:06.019 --> 01:06:09.880
You could make it so safe that you could never
fly or you could never fly cross-country or

01:06:09.880 --> 01:06:11.229
you could never take a train.

01:06:11.229 --> 01:06:12.729
You've got to use some judgment.

01:06:12.729 --> 01:06:22.269
And, of course, that risk today, that risk
level today is not very well accepted.

01:06:22.269 --> 01:06:35.229
A point I was trying to make is that during
the Apollo Program it was accepted.

01:06:35.229 --> 01:06:40.380
We knew we had to take risk.

01:06:40.380 --> 01:06:42.119
Tell me when you want to break, Jeff.

01:06:42.119 --> 01:06:44.799
Do you want to break now?

01:06:44.799 --> 01:06:45.799
This is probably a good time.

01:06:45.799 --> 01:06:46.799
OK.

01:06:46.799 --> 01:06:47.799
We will take about a five minute break.

01:06:47.799 --> 01:06:48.799
I want to get to cost, but I have got a few
more things to say.

01:06:48.799 --> 01:06:49.799
Let me talk about process.

01:06:49.799 --> 01:06:53.369
We had a contract with Ford Motor Company,
and I showed this to Ford Motor Company of

01:06:53.369 --> 01:06:54.369
a design process I would go through.

01:06:54.369 --> 01:06:57.099
And they said that is very interesting, we
studied for a long time and this is exactly

01:06:57.099 --> 01:07:04.130
what we use to understand the need.

01:07:04.130 --> 01:07:05.130
And the need was not the Ford Edsel.

01:07:05.130 --> 01:07:07.680
That was not a good needs statement.

01:07:07.680 --> 01:07:16.920
But you need a need, you need a need analysis
[OVERLAPPING VOICES].

01:07:16.920 --> 01:07:19.430
Well, I tell you.

01:07:19.430 --> 01:07:20.869
You need to talk to Henry Pohl.

01:07:20.869 --> 01:07:23.450
Henry Pohl, who heard lecture, still has an
Edsel.

01:07:23.450 --> 01:07:28.289
Henry is probably one of the few people that
still has an Edsel in his garage.

01:07:28.289 --> 01:07:34.450
Henry has a lot of things like that, but Henry
still has an Edsel.

01:07:34.450 --> 01:07:38.130
But you need to do a need analysis, understand
what the need means.

01:07:38.130 --> 01:07:39.160
You need a function structure.

01:07:39.160 --> 01:07:45.890
And, actually, in some of your reports I saw
very good examples of all these.

01:07:45.890 --> 01:07:50.940
Now, maybe not in all the reports, but I saw
somebody talking about the needs, somebody

01:07:50.940 --> 01:07:55.999
talking about needs analysis, somebody talking
about function structure requirements.

01:07:55.999 --> 01:08:01.489
The hardest thing for engineers to do, especially
young engineers to do, is to make some assumptions

01:08:01.489 --> 01:08:04.619
and constraints and do some preliminary calculations.

01:08:04.619 --> 01:08:07.299
It is very difficult for them to do that.

01:08:07.299 --> 01:08:09.130
They like to see F=ma.

