01:10:28.600 --> 01:10:31.750
Let me talk a little bit about cost estimation
techniques.

01:10:31.750 --> 01:10:33.561
It turns out some of you were trying to use
it.

01:10:33.561 --> 01:10:38.520
Here are the cost estimating techniques.

01:10:38.520 --> 01:10:39.880
Expert interview.

01:10:39.880 --> 01:10:43.410
You talk to an expert in the field, if you
can find one.

01:10:43.410 --> 01:10:44.410
Parametric analysis.

01:10:44.410 --> 01:10:48.210
I am going to spend most of my time talking
about parametric cost analysis because I think

01:10:48.210 --> 01:10:52.010
that is the one that pertains to an engineering
design course.

01:10:52.010 --> 01:10:53.010
Parametrics.

01:10:53.010 --> 01:10:57.920
Because it is in terms that you understand,
weight, performance, that type of thing.

01:10:57.920 --> 01:11:02.340
I am going to talk about that.

01:11:02.340 --> 01:11:03.340
Analogies.

01:11:03.340 --> 01:11:08.870
And then the engineering which is really,
you might say, the grassroots or the buildup

01:11:08.870 --> 01:11:13.670
of what it is going to cost for engineering
hours, manufacturing hours and that type of

01:11:13.670 --> 01:11:14.930
thing, which is pretty hard to do.

01:11:14.930 --> 01:11:16.190
I am going to go through those.

01:11:16.190 --> 01:11:18.480
Now, some of you have tried to do some of
these.

01:11:18.480 --> 01:11:23.340
Some of you have tried to call contractors
to find out what a particular thing was going

01:11:23.340 --> 01:11:24.340
to cost.

01:11:24.340 --> 01:11:28.770
Some of you have tried to find out what the
Shuttle Guidance and Navigation System cost.

01:11:28.770 --> 01:11:32.060
You were trying to do it, but it's not easy
to come by.

01:11:32.060 --> 01:11:35.610
You call a vendor and he says well, he will
quote you, but he wants to know what you're

01:11:35.610 --> 01:11:36.610
going to use it for.

01:11:36.610 --> 01:11:37.610
It is hard to do.

01:11:37.610 --> 01:11:38.751
I know it is very, very hard to do.

01:11:38.751 --> 01:11:44.740
And they want to know how many hundred you
are going to buy.

01:11:44.740 --> 01:11:50.170
I don't minimize the job you have in trying
to do a cost estimate, but you've got to recognize

01:11:50.170 --> 01:11:54.760
that, as an engineer and you go out and start
to work, they are going to want to know what

01:11:54.760 --> 01:12:01.980
this thing is going to cost you and what allies
you have to make.

01:12:01.980 --> 01:12:08.750
Now, these are the cost estimating techniques
over the project cycles.

01:12:08.750 --> 01:12:15.690
You can see, as the project goes along, you
have this so-called parametric method, analogies,

01:12:15.690 --> 01:12:20.280
judgments, system level CERs, cost estimate
relationships.

01:12:20.280 --> 01:12:22.780
And that is a very key thing, cost estimate
relationships.

01:12:22.780 --> 01:12:26.600
I am going to talk more about that, but let
me tell you what a cost estimate relationship

01:12:26.600 --> 01:12:28.640
in a very simple-minded approach is.

01:12:28.640 --> 01:12:31.980
Let's say you're going to go buy a house.

01:12:31.980 --> 01:12:34.610
What is the first thing you want to know about
buying a house?

01:12:34.610 --> 01:12:37.280
How many square feet do you have, right?

01:12:37.280 --> 01:12:41.960
You take how many square feet you're going
to have and you usually know about what it

01:12:41.960 --> 01:12:46.310
cost per square foot in the area you want
to buy a house in.

01:12:46.310 --> 01:12:48.521
You multiply that and you get a rough estimate
of the house.

01:12:48.521 --> 01:12:51.180
Now, there is another factor that goes into
that.

01:12:51.180 --> 01:12:52.580
There is the culture.

01:12:52.580 --> 01:12:57.040
Where you are going to build this house is
going to affect the cost per square foot.

01:12:57.040 --> 01:13:01.070
If you build it in a very expensive neighborhood
-- I always give the relationship in Houston

01:13:01.070 --> 01:13:02.070
because I know Houston.

01:13:02.070 --> 01:13:07.350
If you're going to build it in Clear Lake
where NASA is, it is one culture.

01:13:07.350 --> 01:13:12.640
If you build it in River Oaks where the very
wealth oil people, it is another culture.

01:13:12.640 --> 01:13:17.600
The cost per square foot in Clear Lake is
much lower than the cost per square foot in

01:13:17.600 --> 01:13:18.670
Clear Lake.

01:13:18.670 --> 01:13:21.630
You can get a rough estimate, but that is
a very simple-minded CER.

01:13:21.630 --> 01:13:23.390
It is a cost estimate relationship.

01:13:23.390 --> 01:13:27.790
They become very, very complicated when you
talk about past history, when you talk about

01:13:27.790 --> 01:13:29.330
weight of spacecraft and so forth and so on.

01:13:29.330 --> 01:13:31.430
I will develop a little bit of that.

01:13:31.430 --> 01:13:34.600
General subsystem CERs and calibrated system
CERs.

01:13:34.600 --> 01:13:36.400
But these are the parametric methods.

01:13:36.400 --> 01:13:41.310
And you can see where they are used, analogies
and judgment.

01:13:41.310 --> 01:13:43.410
And they are used for a certain period of
time.

01:13:43.410 --> 01:13:54.060
Then, when you get to the phase B or CD, you
talk about component buildup estimates, detailed

01:13:54.060 --> 01:13:56.880
estimates and vendor quotes.

01:13:56.880 --> 01:13:58.920
That is sort of the schedule.

01:13:58.920 --> 01:14:04.260
And this was provided by the cost technology
over the project cycles by the Lunar and Mars

01:14:04.260 --> 01:14:05.260
Exploration Office.

01:14:05.260 --> 01:14:07.520
That goes way back.

01:14:07.520 --> 01:14:09.540
It has abolished and now restored again.

01:14:09.540 --> 01:14:13.610
So, that is the cycle you go through.

01:14:13.610 --> 01:14:19.750
And, of course, you're in really the phase
A so it is going to be pretty hard for you

01:14:19.750 --> 01:14:21.830
to do the direct methods.

01:14:21.830 --> 01:14:25.190
Even though you might try, it is going to
be pretty hard for you to do that.

01:14:25.190 --> 01:14:26.670
You almost have to use some type of a parametrics.

01:14:26.670 --> 01:14:30.060
And I am going to talk about how you do a
parametric.

01:14:30.060 --> 01:14:39.020
I am going to talk to you about how you do
both of them.

01:14:39.020 --> 01:14:41.750
And this can get you into more trouble.

01:14:41.750 --> 01:14:46.210
Cost estimates get you in a lot of trouble.

01:14:46.210 --> 01:14:52.190
How many in here are familiar with what we
call a work breakdown structure?

01:14:52.190 --> 01:14:53.550
OK, good.

01:14:53.550 --> 01:14:59.691
Work breakdown structure is really the management
tool that is needed in doing a project.

01:14:59.691 --> 01:15:05.940
Whenever you get a project you form a work
breakdown structure which is a hierarchical

01:15:05.940 --> 01:15:08.920
breakdown, the work necessary to complete
a project.

01:15:08.920 --> 01:15:12.960
Work breakdown structure elements should be
identified by title, by numbering system that

01:15:12.960 --> 01:15:14.290
performs the following functions.

01:15:14.290 --> 01:15:19.240
It identifies the level of the breakdown structure
element, it identifies the higher level to

01:15:19.240 --> 01:15:22.470
which the breakdown structure would be integrated
and shows the cost.

01:15:22.470 --> 01:15:23.470
That is the key thing.

01:15:23.470 --> 01:15:28.120
It shows the cost account number of the element
and how much it costs, how much labor hours

01:15:28.120 --> 01:15:29.120
is going to take.

01:15:29.120 --> 01:15:32.430
That is a very, very important tool.

01:15:32.430 --> 01:15:37.350
In fact, when you go out and work in industry,
actually, if you become a member of a work

01:15:37.350 --> 01:15:41.240
breakdown structure, you're graded on how
well you perform under this work breakdown

01:15:41.240 --> 01:15:42.240
structure.

01:15:42.240 --> 01:15:43.240
That is the tool they grade you on.

01:15:43.240 --> 01:15:45.040
We will put these charts on the Internet.

01:15:45.040 --> 01:15:48.890
Roll of the work breakdown structure.

01:15:48.890 --> 01:15:53.450
Project and technical planning and scheduling.

01:15:53.450 --> 01:15:55.140
Cost estimating and budget formulation.

01:15:55.140 --> 01:15:59.740
Project status reporting and plans such as
specifications and drawings.

01:15:59.740 --> 01:16:04.010
Now, those that raised their hands, where
did you learn to do work breakdown structure?

01:16:04.010 --> 01:16:05.570
Can anybody answer me?

01:16:05.570 --> 01:16:09.560
Where did you learn to do that, those that
said you were familiar with it?

01:16:09.560 --> 01:16:11.230
Yes, sir.

01:16:11.230 --> 01:16:13.270
I learned it here at MIT.

01:16:13.270 --> 01:16:14.270
Did you?

01:16:14.270 --> 01:16:15.270
Very good.

01:16:15.270 --> 01:16:16.270
They taught you.

01:16:16.270 --> 01:16:17.270
That's very good.

01:16:17.270 --> 01:16:18.270
What course was it?

01:16:18.270 --> 01:16:19.270
It is not a course.

01:16:19.270 --> 01:16:20.270
It is my research.

01:16:20.270 --> 01:16:21.270
Oh, your research.

01:16:21.270 --> 01:16:24.690
Did you find it hard to do?

01:16:24.690 --> 01:16:34.340
I found it initially difficult, but once I
realized how to work it, I definitely saw

01:16:34.340 --> 01:16:36.152
the benefits of that approach.

01:16:36.152 --> 01:16:37.152
Very good.

01:16:37.152 --> 01:16:38.152
Well, it is an important tool that you need
to do.

01:16:38.152 --> 01:16:42.080
And that is why it is probably a little hard
for you to do cost estimation because you

01:16:42.080 --> 01:16:47.740
are not used to some of these things you need
to do to get the cost done.

01:16:47.740 --> 01:16:56.190
Well, some of the basic elements of cost estimation
is understand the product, develop a detailed

01:16:56.190 --> 01:16:57.450
work breakdown structure.

01:16:57.450 --> 01:16:58.450
Did you do that for this project?

01:16:58.450 --> 01:16:59.450
No.

01:16:59.450 --> 01:17:00.450
That is OK.

01:17:00.450 --> 01:17:05.650
I didn't mean to put you under the gun.

01:17:05.650 --> 01:17:07.300
Understand the development of the culture.

01:17:07.300 --> 01:17:08.720
Understand the culture.

01:17:08.720 --> 01:17:16.360
It turns out the NASA culture is pretty high
level because it does involve risk.

01:17:16.360 --> 01:17:21.710
And I will give you a little story about.

01:17:21.710 --> 01:17:28.710
Somebody asked von Braun one time why NASA
had to gold plate everything.

01:17:28.710 --> 01:17:33.700
He said because you made it out of pure gold
it would cost too much.

01:17:33.700 --> 01:17:40.440
It is not that they gold plate everything,
but it is that you really have a life concern

01:17:40.440 --> 01:17:43.010
in a very hostile environment.

01:17:43.010 --> 01:17:46.070
You have to understand the development culture.

01:17:46.070 --> 01:17:50.580
Gather data from close analogs, develop the
cost estimate relationships.

01:17:50.580 --> 01:17:54.640
There are textbooks that show you how to develop
CERs.

01:17:54.640 --> 01:17:59.530
There is a large society called parametric
cost analysis.

01:17:59.530 --> 01:18:00.920
And in that you can get how to develop CERs.

01:18:00.920 --> 01:18:06.790
I am not suggesting you necessarily do that
because it is very, very time consuming, but

01:18:06.790 --> 01:18:09.010
just know that they do exist.

01:18:09.010 --> 01:18:14.480
There are, by the way, very sophisticated
computer programs, which I want to talk about,

01:18:14.480 --> 01:18:18.390
that develop the CERs for you based on inputs
you give them.

01:18:18.390 --> 01:18:20.190
These programs are very expensive.

01:18:20.190 --> 01:18:21.630
One is called PRICE.

01:18:21.630 --> 01:18:24.980
I will show you what the other one is.

01:18:24.980 --> 01:18:28.040
And it was actually developed by RCA.

01:18:28.040 --> 01:18:31.250
It now is owned by the Martin Company.

01:18:31.250 --> 01:18:35.230
Or was owned by the Martin Company.

01:18:35.230 --> 01:18:38.321
Group CERs according to the work breakdown
structure.

01:18:38.321 --> 01:18:41.270
And you need to quantify the risk and the
method.

01:18:41.270 --> 01:18:43.820
Estimate the cost, spread the cost and do
a reality check.

01:18:43.820 --> 01:18:45.600
Those are some of the things you need to do.

01:18:45.600 --> 01:19:00.750
Now, understanding the costing and the analysis
process, as I said, you need to understand

01:19:00.750 --> 01:19:04.400
the project, participate in the design team
activities.

01:19:04.400 --> 01:19:07.750
Scoping, inheritance and complexity.

01:19:07.750 --> 01:19:12.330
Identification of content, schedule and goals.

01:19:12.330 --> 01:19:18.760
Collecting cost, estimating inputs by weight
statements, technical characteristics, preparing

01:19:18.760 --> 01:19:23.250
the estimates, CERs, translating labor hours
and dollar hours.

01:19:23.250 --> 01:19:29.291
And this is a lot of details that you are
not going to have time to do, but you do need

01:19:29.291 --> 01:19:33.790
to understand the complexity that doing cost
analysis entails.

01:19:33.790 --> 01:19:36.600
It is very, very difficult and very hard to
do.

01:19:36.600 --> 01:19:39.100
And you have groups set up to do that.

01:19:39.100 --> 01:19:44.390
But, on the other hand, engineers working
on a project are going to be called upon to

01:19:44.390 --> 01:19:48.640
do it because you are the best source of information
that they have to do it.

01:19:48.640 --> 01:20:04.272
Here is the basic building block of the parametric
cost estimating, is the relationship of the

01:20:04.272 --> 01:20:05.561
cost estimating relationship.

01:20:05.561 --> 01:20:10.000
And the dependent value variable is cost.

01:20:10.000 --> 01:20:13.870
The independent variable is something that
you can understand.

01:20:13.870 --> 01:20:16.420
It is weight, power, ISP and so forth.

01:20:16.420 --> 01:20:17.420
They are specific engineering terms.

01:20:17.420 --> 01:20:26.560
And there is some relationship between weight,
certainly for structures, there is certainly

01:20:26.560 --> 01:20:35.270
a value based on historical data points of
weight of the structure, the type of materials

01:20:35.270 --> 01:20:38.770
and so forth on the CER, the cost relationship.

01:20:38.770 --> 01:20:41.420
So, that is how it is developed.

01:20:41.420 --> 01:20:46.290
A lot of students had a very difficult time
using this program because they didn't know

01:20:46.290 --> 01:20:48.080
how the CERs were developed.

01:20:48.080 --> 01:20:52.239
It frustrated them because here was this magic
program that calculated the CERs for them.

01:20:52.239 --> 01:20:53.239
Right, Josh?

01:20:53.239 --> 01:20:55.270
Josh is one of my students.

01:20:55.270 --> 01:20:58.880
And they had a very difficult time trying
to understand how to use the program because

01:20:58.880 --> 01:21:02.670
they couldn't understand how to do the CERs.

01:21:02.670 --> 01:21:04.820
But there is a methodology in it.

01:21:04.820 --> 01:21:06.440
And there are many books that explain it.

01:21:06.440 --> 01:21:11.340
The other thing that is important, as I pointed
out, is the cultural variable.

01:21:11.340 --> 01:21:16.330
The cultural variable is this.

01:21:16.330 --> 01:21:20.060
See, this is one, unit dry weight.

01:21:20.060 --> 01:21:24.820
And it can show us the total cost, but it
can show that for aircraft you're on one culture

01:21:24.820 --> 01:21:29.920
plane, on an unmanned spacecraft you're on
another cultural plane, on manned spacecraft

01:21:29.920 --> 01:21:36.310
you're on another cultural plane and on a
planetary spacecraft you're on another cultural

01:21:36.310 --> 01:21:37.310
plane.

01:21:37.310 --> 01:21:38.690
That is a very big issue.

01:21:38.690 --> 01:21:43.170
One of the issues with NASA they say, to get
the cost down for NASA, is you need to change

01:21:43.170 --> 01:21:44.170
the cultural plane.

01:21:44.170 --> 01:21:48.200
Of course, if you change the cultural plane
you probably have to give up something.

01:21:48.200 --> 01:21:53.370
You probably would give up some risk in terms
of safety or margin.

01:21:53.370 --> 01:21:58.800
So, you have got to recognize that the cultural
variable is a very strong indicator.

01:21:58.800 --> 01:22:02.110
Are you happy to note that the aircraft is
so low and everybody flies on an airplane,

01:22:02.110 --> 01:22:06.020
but that is the cultural variable that it
shows.

01:22:06.020 --> 01:22:15.920
For a structure, you can see how the structure
varies based on the cultural plane.

01:22:15.920 --> 01:22:22.590
When you were talking about like using square
footage as a rough estimate for a house, and

01:22:22.590 --> 01:22:31.010
in the space business we do use weight as
kind of a substitute.

01:22:31.010 --> 01:22:33.400
You can translate from weight into cost.

01:22:33.400 --> 01:22:39.790
And yet people always point out, well, yeah,
but a kilogram of aluminum structure costs

01:22:39.790 --> 01:22:44.260
a lot less than a kilogram of computer chips.

01:22:44.260 --> 01:22:48.790
But, nevertheless, when you put everything
down when you're designing a planetary spacecraft,

01:22:48.790 --> 01:22:51.190
they do have these estimated relationships.

01:22:51.190 --> 01:23:00.990
If you're going to have a project which lands
150 kilograms on Mars compared to a ton on

01:23:00.990 --> 01:23:03.960
Mars, we do have these relationships.

01:23:03.960 --> 01:23:10.260
Because, in general, we figure that the ratio
of hardware and software and computer chips

01:23:10.260 --> 01:23:14.230
to aluminum and all that is roughly similar.

01:23:14.230 --> 01:23:19.510
But if you are going to try to build something
that is fundamentally new, which involves

01:23:19.510 --> 01:23:26.170
a lot of new technology, then of course you
can go way off of these rough estimates.

01:23:26.170 --> 01:23:31.310
To get a good understanding, you might say
a very quick understanding, you might go to

01:23:31.310 --> 01:23:36.770
the NASA website and get parametric cost analysis.

01:23:36.770 --> 01:23:40.420
It will give you a very good understanding
of what you can get.

01:23:40.420 --> 01:23:44.670
And you can get some of these programs off
the Internet today.

01:23:44.670 --> 01:23:51.200
They are not very sophisticated but they do
have some CER relationships, as Jeff was talking

01:23:51.200 --> 01:23:52.200
about.

01:23:52.200 --> 01:23:58.320
It might be a little bit more difficult for
some of the items.

01:23:58.320 --> 01:23:59.850
Structures would be an easy item to do but,
unfortunately, I don't think anybody is doing

01:23:59.850 --> 01:24:00.850
that.

01:24:00.850 --> 01:24:01.870
But it would even be good for the avionics
system, I think, in life support.

01:24:01.870 --> 01:24:02.870
Yes.

01:24:02.870 --> 01:24:05.220
Are these software packages basically just
a large database?

01:24:05.220 --> 01:24:12.611
They are basically a large database that you
put in the data.

01:24:12.611 --> 01:24:20.230
In fact, they are so sophisticated now, you
can put in the software, the type of software

01:24:20.230 --> 01:24:24.310
you are using, the number of lines of code
and, based on the CER for that particular

01:24:24.310 --> 01:24:28.760
subject, it can tell you how much it is going
to cost per line of code.

01:24:28.760 --> 01:24:31.210
It is very, very sophisticated.

01:24:31.210 --> 01:24:32.210
And NASA uses it quite a bit.

01:24:32.210 --> 01:24:33.210
Yes?

01:24:33.210 --> 01:24:41.310
With this software, you must have to update
it very, very frequently because of technology

01:24:41.310 --> 01:24:42.480
changes.

01:24:42.480 --> 01:24:44.980
They update it very frequently.

01:24:44.980 --> 01:24:45.980
That's right.

01:24:45.980 --> 01:24:46.980
And that is why they are so expensive.

01:24:46.980 --> 01:24:48.710
They are very expensive, but they update them.

01:24:48.710 --> 01:24:52.950
For example, I started using it at A&amp;M, and
they didn't have even a software package in

01:24:52.950 --> 01:24:53.950
there for composites.

01:24:53.950 --> 01:24:55.100
Now they have one for composites.

01:24:55.100 --> 01:25:03.711
And there are a lot of these which are proprietary
and you cannot even get access to them.

01:25:03.711 --> 01:25:12.330
I mean the Aerospace Corporation has compiled
a huge database of costs of a lot of components

01:25:12.330 --> 01:25:16.950
historical to how much it was estimated, how
much it actually cost.

01:25:16.950 --> 01:25:23.580
And so NASA and the DOD often go to Aerospace
to do cost analysis for them.

01:25:23.580 --> 01:25:25.100
And, of course, Aerospace charges.

01:25:25.100 --> 01:25:30.390
And they don't release their database because
it is proprietary.

01:25:30.390 --> 01:25:35.090
Knowledge is power and money in this situation.

01:25:35.090 --> 01:25:47.440
They put a lot of work into putting the database
together.

01:25:47.440 --> 01:25:48.440
Yes.

01:25:48.440 --> 01:25:49.440
[AUDIENCE QUESTION]

01:25:49.440 --> 01:25:50.440
Were you able to try to use it?

01:25:50.440 --> 01:25:51.470
Did you try to check it out?

01:25:51.470 --> 01:25:54.850
[AUDIENCE QUESTION]

01:25:54.850 --> 01:26:00.110
And, of course, it may not have the update
as this gentleman was talking about, but it

01:26:00.110 --> 01:26:01.460
has a certain amount.

01:26:01.460 --> 01:26:03.400
You could do a pretty quick analysis.

01:26:03.400 --> 01:26:11.460
I would suggest you try to do that because
I know that I had looked at it, and there

01:26:11.460 --> 01:26:12.460
are ways to do it.

01:26:12.460 --> 01:26:15.150
Now, you've got to be careful of the results
because sometimes the results become pretty

01:26:15.150 --> 01:26:16.150
high.

01:26:16.150 --> 01:26:22.790
But you've got to be careful of the results
and look at it pretty carefully.

01:26:22.790 --> 01:26:25.830
This is another development of cost scaling
law.

01:26:25.830 --> 01:26:33.380
This happens to be weight versus -- You can
see the two different cultural planes, known

01:26:33.380 --> 01:26:36.680
cost and weight, unknown cost from a given
weight.

01:26:36.680 --> 01:26:39.320
This is basically how they generate the CERs.

01:26:39.320 --> 01:26:40.500
It is a process.

01:26:40.500 --> 01:26:43.860
It isn't an analytical process, but there
also is a lot of empirical data that goes

01:26:43.860 --> 01:26:45.480
with it.

01:26:45.480 --> 01:26:52.330
And, as Jeff said, it is based on a large
database.

01:26:52.330 --> 01:26:59.600
Now, cost estimation, I am telling you hard
it is to do and you probably already know

01:26:59.600 --> 01:27:00.600
it.

01:27:00.600 --> 01:27:05.050
But, for a cost estimation, now, this is after
you get over the errors of parametric cost

01:27:05.050 --> 01:27:06.050
analysis.

01:27:06.050 --> 01:27:10.880
Now we're talking about how you do a cost
analysis when you're really trying to figure

01:27:10.880 --> 01:27:15.760
how you go forward to ask for a budget.

01:27:15.760 --> 01:27:18.280
You need fairly detailed information.

01:27:18.280 --> 01:27:23.010
It is unrealistic for designers to give cost
information for conceptualist designs, but

01:27:23.010 --> 01:27:27.230
designers must be able to make rough cost
estimates.

01:27:27.230 --> 01:27:33.160
That is what I am saying, that you do need
to be able to make rough cost estimates.

01:27:33.160 --> 01:27:39.582
Now, if you are trying to make a detailed
cost estimate, and that goes back to the work

01:27:39.582 --> 01:27:45.571
breakdown structure, you need the number of
labor hours and number of people on the project.

01:27:45.571 --> 01:27:49.590
I mean people is probably going to be the
most expensive.

01:27:49.590 --> 01:27:55.350
You need the number of labor hours, the number
of people on the project.

01:27:55.350 --> 01:27:59.630
During the Shuttle Program, Orbiter Project
Manager, I used to call my counterpart at

01:27:59.630 --> 01:28:01.390
Rockwell every Saturday morning.

01:28:01.390 --> 01:28:07.240
And we would go through how many people we
had on each work breakdown structure for each

01:28:07.240 --> 01:28:08.240
contractor.

01:28:08.240 --> 01:28:12.570
We would talk about it to be sure we had the
budget to cover it.

01:28:12.570 --> 01:28:15.430
And then, of course, we had to be sure we
got the product out the door.

01:28:15.430 --> 01:28:19.580
But the number of labor hours, the number
of people on the project, the length of time

01:28:19.580 --> 01:28:24.560
these people are going to be on it, the overhead
rates, office space, computer, benefits, cost

01:28:24.560 --> 01:28:28.261
per hour of a person basically is what you
are looking for, that is how you really do

01:28:28.261 --> 01:28:30.130
a cost estimate.

01:28:30.130 --> 01:28:35.670
And, of course, it is going to vary, depending
on the locale of the contractor.

01:28:35.670 --> 01:28:36.670
What are the cost drivers?

01:28:36.670 --> 01:28:44.290
Now, here is where the cost comes out, some
of the things that Dr.

01:28:44.290 --> 01:28:45.290
Hoffman was talking about.

01:28:45.290 --> 01:28:47.340
The errors in the design.

01:28:47.340 --> 01:28:49.520
Change in requirements.

01:28:49.520 --> 01:28:52.630
Core interface definition.

01:28:52.630 --> 01:28:53.630
Technology development.

01:28:53.630 --> 01:28:54.630
Poor communication.

01:28:54.630 --> 01:28:55.630
Poor teamwork.

01:28:55.630 --> 01:29:02.190
These are all elements of systems engineering
that have gone awry, that have not gone in

01:29:02.190 --> 01:29:03.550
the right direction.

01:29:03.550 --> 01:29:06.140
But this is what caused the cost to go up.

01:29:06.140 --> 01:29:12.090
In my experience, the biggest problem in cost
estimates have been the changes in requirements.

01:29:12.090 --> 01:29:16.710
That is really the thing that has caused most
of the problems.

01:29:16.710 --> 01:29:21.160
That is why you need really good definition
requirements and not change it.

01:29:21.160 --> 01:29:27.020
Technology development, that can cost you
a lot of money and sometimes you have to go

01:29:27.020 --> 01:29:31.590
forward with it.

01:29:31.590 --> 01:29:39.280
Now, this is old data.

01:29:39.280 --> 01:29:43.150
This is 1993 data, but I got this from a contractor
a long time ago.

01:29:43.150 --> 01:29:47.440
First of all what you need to do, and of course
it is a lot different, I don't know if it

01:29:47.440 --> 01:29:48.440
is higher or lower today with CAD systems,
this was before they really used CAD systems,

01:29:48.440 --> 01:29:49.440
but this the average cost of an engineering
drawing.

01:29:49.440 --> 01:29:52.200
And it goes through how you do it.

01:29:52.200 --> 01:29:57.110
It is probably the labor rates are higher
today.

01:29:57.110 --> 01:29:59.210
The average hours per drawing are probably
lower.

01:29:59.210 --> 01:30:02.520
But this says in 1993, the rate is an estimate
for 1993 government year of about $3,000 in

01:30:02.520 --> 01:30:05.710
average drawing, so you have to figure out
how many drawings you need.

01:30:05.710 --> 01:30:12.210
I mean that is a good way to understand the
cost estimate of what it is going to be.

01:30:12.210 --> 01:30:18.211
You need to know how many drawings you need
and you need an understanding of the cost

01:30:18.211 --> 01:30:19.211
settlement.

01:30:19.211 --> 01:30:25.030
The elements of cost during manufacturing
then are the number and complexity of the

01:30:25.030 --> 01:30:30.630
drawings, cost of a drawing, number and complexity
of machine and fabricated parts and what the

01:30:30.630 --> 01:30:32.571
parts are made out of.

01:30:32.571 --> 01:30:39.240
Aluminum, steel, titanium, nickel, inconel
and so forth, because some are more complicated

01:30:39.240 --> 01:30:40.760
to machine than others.

01:30:40.760 --> 01:30:46.280
But some are used in the Space Program, some
are not.

01:30:46.280 --> 01:30:50.130
Titanium was becoming more and more important.

01:30:50.130 --> 01:31:00.010
Other things of manufacturing are tolerance
of parts.

01:31:00.010 --> 01:31:04.880
It turns out engineers tend to, you might
say, put extra tolerances on parts that they

01:31:04.880 --> 01:31:05.880
don't need.

01:31:05.880 --> 01:31:08.940
And that can cause parts to be very, very
expensive.

01:31:08.940 --> 01:31:12.880
The finish of parts, the quality of parts,
assembly, complexity and time qualification

01:31:12.880 --> 01:31:13.880
of checking a test.

01:31:13.880 --> 01:31:17.020
I remember my first day at work, when I worked
for RCA, I was designing a microwave tube,

01:31:17.020 --> 01:31:18.020
magnetron.

01:31:18.020 --> 01:31:20.570
I was a terrible draftsman, as a matter of
fact.

01:31:20.570 --> 01:31:21.570
That was a long time ago.

01:31:21.570 --> 01:31:22.570
I would probably be better with CAD systems.

01:31:22.570 --> 01:31:28.760
But I sent out this part to the shop.

01:31:28.760 --> 01:31:39.850
And this guy coming in showing this stogy
out in the machine shop.

01:31:39.850 --> 01:31:45.920
At that time we sat in these big bullpens,
each person at a desk, and I had my name on

01:31:45.920 --> 01:31:46.920
my desk.

01:31:46.920 --> 01:31:53.260
He comes in this big room and says where the
hell is Cohen?

01:31:53.260 --> 01:31:54.260
That is me.

01:31:54.260 --> 01:31:56.930
He said this is the dumbest drawing I have
ever seen in my life.

01:31:56.930 --> 01:31:59.130
How do you expect anybody to make this part?

01:31:59.130 --> 01:32:02.200
So, you have to be sure you understand what
you are doing.

01:32:02.200 --> 01:32:07.920
It turns out I learned to work with that guy
and became good friends.

01:32:07.920 --> 01:32:12.280
That never happened again, but he wanted to
know where the hell was this Cohen who put

01:32:12.280 --> 01:32:13.280
out this dumb drawing?

01:32:13.280 --> 01:32:14.330
He said there is no way I can make this part.

01:32:14.330 --> 01:32:18.581
And that was a small part, but you need to
understand the complexity of the part and

01:32:18.581 --> 01:32:21.680
what you're putting out to the shop.

01:32:21.680 --> 01:32:24.240
But today they have checks and balances.

01:32:24.240 --> 01:32:28.730
And, with the CAD systems, I am not even sure
this is accurate anymore.

01:32:28.730 --> 01:32:32.350
This about brings me to the close of what
I wanted to talk to you about, but let me

01:32:32.350 --> 01:32:34.320
just give you one final chart.

01:32:34.320 --> 01:32:39.090
And then I would like you to ask some questions
about anything I talked about or anything

01:32:39.090 --> 01:32:43.860
anybody else covered that you heard about.

01:32:43.860 --> 01:32:48.220
I would stress that for you today in your
course is to try to use parametric cost analysis.

01:32:48.220 --> 01:32:49.590
That is what I would think you should do.

01:32:49.590 --> 01:32:52.310
At least that is what I think you ought to
do.

01:32:52.310 --> 01:32:54.880
And I think you can get information off the
Internet that will allow you to do something.

01:32:54.880 --> 01:32:56.980
Now, it may not pertain to all projects.

01:32:56.980 --> 01:33:01.990
I am not saying you have to do it, but it
might be the thing to do.

01:33:01.990 --> 01:33:02.990
It is going to be very difficult.

01:33:02.990 --> 01:33:04.420
Doing the right thing by creating a work breakdown
structure in trying to do that, it is going

01:33:04.420 --> 01:33:10.380
to be very difficult for you to do it in this
course.

01:33:10.380 --> 01:33:15.530
But the parametric approach to cost, hardware
costs are not produced from parts less than

01:33:15.530 --> 01:33:17.400
labor tables, so you don't need that.

01:33:17.400 --> 01:33:21.120
They are produced from general measures of
the impact of such items costs and in preparing

01:33:21.120 --> 01:33:26.570
inexpensive and more realistic and manageable
costs based on cost estimating relationships.

01:33:26.570 --> 01:33:31.250
You might want to do some reading on cost
estimating relationships, and there are a

01:33:31.250 --> 01:33:35.180
lot of references to that, just to be sure
you understand what I am talking about and

01:33:35.180 --> 01:33:39.690
what they are so it is not a complete mystery
to you so you get a better feel for what it

01:33:39.690 --> 01:33:40.690
is.

01:33:40.690 --> 01:33:43.990
A lot of textbooks have cost estimating relationships.

01:33:43.990 --> 01:33:51.340
CERs make use of characteristics that can
be readily quantifiable such as weight, size

01:33:51.340 --> 01:33:57.010
and to estimate variables that are difficult
to quantify such as cost and production schedules.

01:33:57.010 --> 01:34:02.400
As I said, parametric models can range from
a simple arithmetical relationship to a sophisticated

01:34:02.400 --> 01:34:08.130
computerized model so they can be very, very
complicated or very simple.

01:34:08.130 --> 01:34:10.700
And I suggest you try to do that.

01:34:10.700 --> 01:34:19.070
Let me just show you what the programs are,
not that you will be able to get them, but

01:34:19.070 --> 01:34:25.410
when you get out of industry, if I can find
them here.

01:34:25.410 --> 01:34:36.930
Well, it may not happen.

01:34:36.930 --> 01:34:39.880
There is certainly a lot of information.

01:34:39.880 --> 01:34:42.060
Here is the price model.

01:34:42.060 --> 01:34:46.270
That is price H.

01:34:46.270 --> 01:34:51.640
And you can actually do structural weight
material types, tolerances.

01:34:51.640 --> 01:34:56.600
You can actually do electronics, digital,
analog technology.

01:34:56.600 --> 01:35:00.780
So, you do have quite a bit of latitude of
what you do.

01:35:00.780 --> 01:35:03.250
Now, you're probably not going to get that
program here because it is pretty expensive

01:35:03.250 --> 01:35:04.250
and pretty hard to do.

01:35:04.250 --> 01:35:07.992
But when you go out in industry or government
there is a very high probability you will

01:35:07.992 --> 01:35:09.930
be using some of these programs.

01:35:09.930 --> 01:35:15.670
And Johnson Space Center uses this one and
the Marshall Space Flight Center uses this

01:35:15.670 --> 01:35:16.670
one, CRH.

01:35:16.670 --> 01:35:26.880
There are two programs that are used by NASA,
I know, and they are becoming more and more

01:35:26.880 --> 01:35:28.400
important as we go ahead.

01:35:28.400 --> 01:35:36.770
Aaron, one thing you haven't discussed in
all this discussion of cost is margin.

01:35:36.770 --> 01:35:43.770
And, as a manager, you have to deal with that,
so maybe you can make a few comments on that.

01:35:43.770 --> 01:35:44.770
Sure.

01:35:44.770 --> 01:35:45.770
Well, let me start off this way.

01:35:45.770 --> 01:35:53.830
What Professor Hoffman is alluding to is that
when you create a budget you want to have

01:35:53.830 --> 01:35:59.500
some type of reserve or margin over and above
your cost estimate.

01:35:59.500 --> 01:36:01.650
And that takes care of several things.

01:36:01.650 --> 01:36:14.290
It takes care of changes, it takes care of
I forgots and it takes care of inefficiencies.

01:36:14.290 --> 01:36:24.720
Studies have found that in a high technology
program for the first time you are about 30%

01:36:24.720 --> 01:36:27.410
inefficient, so you are only about 70% efficient.

01:36:27.410 --> 01:36:30.800
Now, this was data that was taken some time
ago.

01:36:30.800 --> 01:36:38.660
You are 70% efficient, so you need to allow
some type of margin in that for your inefficiencies.

01:36:38.660 --> 01:36:45.550
If you do that and you talk about changes
and you talk about I forgots, your reserve

01:36:45.550 --> 01:36:46.550
becomes very high.

01:36:46.550 --> 01:36:52.120
And normally your boss, the guy that is over
you is not going to let you have that much

01:36:52.120 --> 01:36:57.620
money.

01:36:57.620 --> 01:37:03.470
One of the investigations we had on me during
the Shuttle Program, because my cost was growing,

01:37:03.470 --> 01:37:07.970
a very famous man came in to be head of the
program named General Abrahamson.

01:37:07.970 --> 01:37:11.159
Many of you may have heard of General Abrahamson.

01:37:11.159 --> 01:37:16.510
While he did the investigation, he said, Aaron,
you need a large reserve.

01:37:16.510 --> 01:37:19.320
He didn't know he was going to become manager
of the program.

01:37:19.320 --> 01:37:23.892
When he became manager of the program, I had
this large reserve in there, he was reviewing

01:37:23.892 --> 01:37:28.690
and said you cannot have that much reserve
so he wacked it down.

01:37:28.690 --> 01:37:34.330
But you do need a reserve because you're not
going to make it without a reserve.

01:37:34.330 --> 01:37:43.320
And, I don't know if you noticed or not but
in the papers I gave you on the cost of the

01:37:43.320 --> 01:37:47.360
Shuttle system, it had about a 30% reserve
in there.

01:37:47.360 --> 01:37:53.910
When I did the study for the 90-day study,
I had a 50% reserve in there because I felt

01:37:53.910 --> 01:38:00.770
that was a pretty far out program and you
needed a reserve.

01:38:00.770 --> 01:38:03.794
You need to fight for your reserve, but I
guaranty you're not going to get everything

01:38:03.794 --> 01:38:05.070
you think you need.

01:38:05.070 --> 01:38:06.070
Yes, sir.

01:38:06.070 --> 01:38:10.280
For something like aerospace, every time you
do a cost estimate, they talk about it, look

01:38:10.280 --> 01:38:15.400
at it and say, well, let's increase that by
50% or double it.

01:38:15.400 --> 01:38:19.040
And often, even once you've done that, you
still don't come under budget.

01:38:19.040 --> 01:38:26.340
I mean look at the ISS or the Airbus 380 that
is going out.

01:38:26.340 --> 01:38:27.340
Why?

01:38:27.340 --> 01:38:32.670
Well, again, it is really because -- First
of all, it is primarily for the inefficiencies.

01:38:32.670 --> 01:38:34.970
You just cannot do a high-tech program.

01:38:34.970 --> 01:38:41.130
Look at what it cost to do the Big Dig, to
drive it home.

01:38:41.130 --> 01:38:50.760
It is very difficult to do a good cost estimate,
but that is the problem that Congress sees

01:38:50.760 --> 01:38:56.420
with government programs today, both the Department
of Defense and NASA, that they cannot do a

01:38:56.420 --> 01:39:00.530
good cost estimate.

01:39:00.530 --> 01:39:06.710
The current program says they are going to
do the CEVing and go to the Moon for $104

01:39:06.710 --> 01:39:15.610
billion, which is 55% of what it cost to do
the Apollo Program in current year dollars.

01:39:15.610 --> 01:39:17.478
And that is going to be interesting to see
if they can do it.

01:39:17.478 --> 01:39:18.970
It is tough to do.

01:39:18.970 --> 01:39:21.650
But really I think the biggest problem is
your inefficiencies.

01:39:21.650 --> 01:39:30.170
Of course there are changes and I forgots.

01:39:30.170 --> 01:39:34.690
Interesting enough, though, you may or may
not believe this, and you probably won't but

01:39:34.690 --> 01:39:40.450
I will say it anyway, it turns out that the
studies done for the Shuttle Program, for

01:39:40.450 --> 01:39:48.990
the Orbiter actually, in real year dollars,
met the cost if we would have gotten the inflation

01:39:48.990 --> 01:39:50.370
rate.

01:39:50.370 --> 01:39:55.520
We lost the inflation for two years, which
Dale Myers fought for vigorously with OMB.

01:39:55.520 --> 01:40:01.660
If we would have gotten the inflation for
those two years, we would have met cost for

01:40:01.660 --> 01:40:02.680
the development cost.

01:40:02.680 --> 01:40:05.530
Not for the operational cost, but for the
development cost we would have come pretty

01:40:05.530 --> 01:40:06.890
close to it.

01:40:06.890 --> 01:40:08.930
We didn't really miss it that far.

01:40:08.930 --> 01:40:13.260
In Apollo, I'm not sure, you would need to
ask Dr.

01:40:13.260 --> 01:40:18.100
Siemens, but the story goes is that NASA came
in with an estimate.

01:40:18.100 --> 01:40:22.320
And at that time the administrator, Webb,
looked at it and said that is fine and he

01:40:22.320 --> 01:40:25.540
doubled it, and so Apollo did very well.

01:40:25.540 --> 01:40:28.751
I think Bob Siemens has told that.

01:40:28.751 --> 01:40:35.600
The story we heard was it was on their way
over to the White House that he said our final

01:40:35.600 --> 01:40:40.310
estimate, we've put all the factors and everything
in, is $10 billion.

01:40:40.310 --> 01:40:43.580
And Webb said, OK, we will tell the President
$20 billion.

01:40:43.580 --> 01:40:46.520
I am sure Bob Siemens would know.

01:40:46.520 --> 01:40:47.520
Yes, sir.

01:40:47.520 --> 01:40:52.130
Aaron, I wanted to ask you about the location
of the reserves.

01:40:52.130 --> 01:41:00.440
Not just dollar reserves, but my experience
as a payload [NOISE OBSCURES].

01:41:00.440 --> 01:41:11.920
The model I have been faced with is that the
mission manager has a reserve for crew time

01:41:11.920 --> 01:41:16.120
or for weight of something but, down on the
project level, you would really like to go

01:41:16.120 --> 01:41:17.780
and have your own.

01:41:17.780 --> 01:41:22.740
And so there was a tendency for everybody
but the lowest level, from the individual

01:41:22.740 --> 01:41:27.250
experiment up to say, well, I am going to
put in a little bit of pad rather than count

01:41:27.250 --> 01:41:32.150
on the fact that I can go up to the mission
manager and ask him for some reserve later.

01:41:32.150 --> 01:41:33.610
Well, that is the danger with that.

01:41:33.610 --> 01:41:34.660
You are absolutely right.

01:41:34.660 --> 01:41:36.121
Everybody would like to put their own reserve
in.

01:41:36.121 --> 01:41:42.710
Of course, being a project manager, I thought
the reserve ought to be at my level.

01:41:42.710 --> 01:41:50.800
But actually, John Yardley was my boss in
Washington, and he thought he should handle

01:41:50.800 --> 01:41:52.270
the reserve.

01:41:52.270 --> 01:41:56.840
And the subsystems managers wanted their reserve,
right?

01:41:56.840 --> 01:41:58.260
Wanted their reserve.

01:41:58.260 --> 01:42:02.760
And John Yardley was another person I should
have mentioned.

01:42:02.760 --> 01:42:07.630
John actually basically pulled the reserve
up and handled it in Washington.

01:42:07.630 --> 01:42:13.711
There is a certain efficiency, I assume, in
having all the reserves centralized so that

01:42:13.711 --> 01:42:17.800
there is not a lot of waste down to lower
levels, but you have to have the confidence

01:42:17.800 --> 01:42:20.070
that you are going to be able to draw on it.

01:42:20.070 --> 01:42:21.070
Right.

01:42:21.070 --> 01:42:24.810
And with that John would partial out some.

01:42:24.810 --> 01:42:31.340
What he would do is be sure that you weren't
double reserving him or triple reserving him.

01:42:31.340 --> 01:42:33.010
And then he would allocate it to me.

01:42:33.010 --> 01:42:34.880
I know he had a rule of thumb.

01:42:34.880 --> 01:42:45.740
When JR Thompson went up, you heard JR talk,
he always asked for more than he needed, so

01:42:45.740 --> 01:42:46.740
John would give him less.

01:42:46.740 --> 01:42:49.530
When I went up, I always asked for less than
I needed, so he would give me more.

01:42:49.530 --> 01:42:52.260
He had a good feel for his managers.

01:42:52.260 --> 01:42:59.100
That is what he told JR one day.

01:42:59.100 --> 01:43:01.021
Normally, you wind up handling it.

01:43:01.021 --> 01:43:04.980
If you have a good program manager at the
top you normally wind up handling it there

01:43:04.980 --> 01:43:08.120
and he parcels it out based on the fact there
is no double bookkeeping.

01:43:08.120 --> 01:43:09.120
Yes.

01:43:09.120 --> 01:43:15.990
My experience at Draper is typically there
are two different ways of estimating.

01:43:15.990 --> 01:43:18.671
One was called top down and the other was
bottoms up.

01:43:18.671 --> 01:43:26.100
And traditionally bottoms up would always
stick their reserve in some way and top down

01:43:26.100 --> 01:43:30.260
would always say I want to know what your
reserves are because I want to bring it up

01:43:30.260 --> 01:43:31.260
to the top.

01:43:31.260 --> 01:43:33.560
And that was a constant argument.

01:43:33.560 --> 01:43:40.260
Then when you got to submitting your proposal
often the customer didn't want to know about

01:43:40.260 --> 01:43:46.640
this extra money and then you would have to
shove it back in and hide it, in a sense,

01:43:46.640 --> 01:43:47.640
by padding things.

01:43:47.640 --> 01:43:54.290
Handling costing in reserves is, to some extent,
at least in my experience, a psychological

01:43:54.290 --> 01:43:57.820
thing dealing with customers and your management.

01:43:57.820 --> 01:44:02.920
And it has always been one where you shuffle
that reserve around.

01:44:02.920 --> 01:44:12.030
But this gentleman asked the question about
why does it appear that NASA never can stay

01:44:12.030 --> 01:44:13.030
on their budget?

01:44:13.030 --> 01:44:15.470
That is really a tough question to answer.

01:44:15.470 --> 01:44:16.700
I don't know.

01:44:16.700 --> 01:44:26.321
I mean I have a personal feeling on it, but
I think the basic problem you have is that

01:44:26.321 --> 01:44:29.591
it is a high technology program.

01:44:29.591 --> 01:44:35.880
It is one of a kind and it is a lot of inefficiencies.

01:44:35.880 --> 01:44:41.080
When you come to work every day, you don't
know exactly what you are going to do.

01:44:41.080 --> 01:44:42.970
You have a technology development that costs.

01:44:42.970 --> 01:44:43.970
You have I forgots.

01:44:43.970 --> 01:44:46.240
You have changing requirements.

01:44:46.240 --> 01:44:51.010
Changing requirements are something that systems
engineering ought to be able to control.

01:44:51.010 --> 01:44:55.530
I forgots are something systems engineering
ought to be able to control.

01:44:55.530 --> 01:44:58.900
Inefficiencies, to a certain extent, systems
engineering ought to be able to control.

01:44:58.900 --> 01:45:04.700
That is one of the purposes, in all honesty,
that are concentrating on system engineering

01:45:04.700 --> 01:45:11.360
at such places at MIT and other schools to
allow the future generation of designers and

01:45:11.360 --> 01:45:17.400
developers in working that they can have a
budget and then stay on the budget.

01:45:17.400 --> 01:45:23.640
Maybe in your generation you will be smarter
and able to control it, but it is not going

01:45:23.640 --> 01:45:24.640
to be an easy job.

01:45:24.640 --> 01:45:27.150
That is one thing I would say.

01:45:27.150 --> 01:45:30.280
Let me just make one other comment.

01:45:30.280 --> 01:45:32.391
We cannot estimate too much.

01:45:32.391 --> 01:45:39.640
That you've got to always keep in mind this
triangle of cost, performance, schedule.

01:45:39.640 --> 01:45:46.880
If you are working on a project where the
schedule is fixed like Apollo then that better

01:45:46.880 --> 01:45:51.580
ring the bells to say that I need more reserves.

01:45:51.580 --> 01:45:56.120
And maybe that is what was going on in Jim
Webb's mind when he said if we really have

01:45:56.120 --> 01:46:02.880
to get this done by the end of the decade,
I better make sure that I am not going to

01:46:02.880 --> 01:46:07.300
be constrained by cost and so I will double
it.

01:46:07.300 --> 01:46:14.190
The other thing that you have to take into
account with the performance is how much new

01:46:14.190 --> 01:46:16.500
technology is this program going to require?

01:46:16.500 --> 01:46:21.510
Because the new technology, that is the hardest
thing to estimate the cost.

01:46:21.510 --> 01:46:22.510
That's right.

01:46:22.510 --> 01:46:28.850
And so, if you have a new technology program
then your margins better be big enough to

01:46:28.850 --> 01:46:29.850
accommodate that.

01:46:29.850 --> 01:46:37.680
That is why, for the CEV, they are really
going out of their way to saying, to the maximum

01:46:37.680 --> 01:46:42.890
extent possible, we don't want to develop
new technology for the CEV.

01:46:42.890 --> 01:46:48.770
We want to use Shuttle parts wherever we can,
Apollo heritage.

01:46:48.770 --> 01:46:54.520
We want to build it out of things that we
know and we understand so that we hopefully

01:46:54.520 --> 01:46:59.130
can keep the cost as low as possible.

01:46:59.130 --> 01:47:00.610
And we will see how it all works out.

01:47:00.610 --> 01:47:01.610
Yes, sir.

01:47:01.610 --> 01:47:02.610
It seems to me that you often times have the
pressure to give a cost estimate on the low

01:47:02.610 --> 01:47:04.150
end of what you believe it to actual be just
so the project might be more appealing [NOISE

01:47:04.150 --> 01:47:05.150
OBSCURES].

01:47:05.150 --> 01:47:15.860
That is certainly another part of the 

01:47:15.860 --> 01:47:17.010
whole political thing.

01:47:17.010 --> 01:47:22.880
And not just from the political point of view
of presenting your estimate when NASA presents

01:47:22.880 --> 01:47:29.380
the estimate to Congress, but then you have
the contractors who want to get the contract

01:47:29.380 --> 01:47:30.380
from NASA.

01:47:30.380 --> 01:47:31.820
And you have certainly had experience with
this.

01:47:31.820 --> 01:47:36.930
How do you deal with the contractor who low-balls
and then assumes that they will be able to

01:47:36.930 --> 01:47:38.650
make it up later on?

01:47:38.650 --> 01:47:43.530
Low-balling really should not be tolerated.

01:47:43.530 --> 01:47:47.780
And they try to do that, not tolerating it,
but you are absolutely right.

01:47:47.780 --> 01:47:52.550
When I did this 90-day study, I really felt
they wanted to know what it was going to cost,

01:47:52.550 --> 01:47:56.990
so I had a 55% reserve in there because I
really felt that there were so many unknowns

01:47:56.990 --> 01:47:57.990
with it.

01:47:57.990 --> 01:47:58.990
And, of course, that didn't go over very well.

01:47:58.990 --> 01:48:02.510
They said my study actually killed the projects.

01:48:02.510 --> 01:48:05.410
But I told them what it was going to cost.

01:48:05.410 --> 01:48:12.862
And then this is a subject for another lecture
entirely, which I am not sure that we are

01:48:12.862 --> 01:48:18.630
going to do in this course, but there are
many different ways to let out contracts,

01:48:18.630 --> 01:48:23.480
fixed price contracts, cost plus contracts,
award contracts.

01:48:23.480 --> 01:48:30.900
And all of those can have an impact on the
ultimate cost of your project.

01:48:30.900 --> 01:48:40.300
And they all have their utility depending
on how well the technology is known and what

01:48:40.300 --> 01:48:42.130
is the time pressure.

01:48:42.130 --> 01:48:45.270
Again, cost, performance, schedule.

01:48:45.270 --> 01:48:49.910
And you asked about Airbus.

01:48:49.910 --> 01:48:54.170
I don't know the specifics of Airbus contracting,
but I am familiar with ESA.

01:48:54.170 --> 01:48:59.220
And, because of some of the peculiarities
of the European system, they tend to use fixed

01:48:59.220 --> 01:49:04.530
price contracts a lot more than we do here.

01:49:04.530 --> 01:49:10.390
And sometimes it works but sometimes you get
really burned on it because contractors are

01:49:10.390 --> 01:49:16.390
not going to go into bankruptcy because they
cannot deliver on their fixed price contracts.

01:49:16.390 --> 01:49:19.720
You try to go fixed price on the CEV and it
would cost you a fortune.

01:49:19.720 --> 01:49:23.400
Those are very good questions.

01:49:23.400 --> 01:49:27.200
Unfortunately, we don't give you very firm
answers on cost.

01:49:27.200 --> 01:49:30.990
But at least you are thinking and I appreciate
your thought process.

01:49:30.990 --> 01:49:35.760
It is very encouraging to hear you ask those
types of questions.

01:49:35.760 --> 01:49:36.760
Have a good weekend.

01:49:36.760 --> 01:49:37.700
We will see you on Tuesday.

